2235    def new_interval_var(
2236        self, start: LinearExprT, size: LinearExprT, end: LinearExprT, name: str
2237    ) -> IntervalVar:
2238        """Creates an interval variable from start, size, and end.
2239
2240        An interval variable is a constraint, that is itself used in other
2241        constraints like NoOverlap.
2242
2243        Internally, it ensures that `start + size == end`.
2244
2245        Args:
2246          start: The start of the interval. It must be of the form a * var + b.
2247          size: The size of the interval. It must be of the form a * var + b.
2248          end: The end of the interval. It must be of the form a * var + b.
2249          name: The name of the interval variable.
2250
2251        Returns:
2252          An `IntervalVar` object.
2253        """
2254
2255        start_expr = self.parse_linear_expression(start)
2256        size_expr = self.parse_linear_expression(size)
2257        end_expr = self.parse_linear_expression(end)
2258        if len(start_expr.vars) > 1:
2259            raise TypeError(
2260                "cp_model.new_interval_var: start must be 1-var affine or constant."
2261            )
2262        if len(size_expr.vars) > 1:
2263            raise TypeError(
2264                "cp_model.new_interval_var: size must be 1-var affine or constant."
2265            )
2266        if len(end_expr.vars) > 1:
2267            raise TypeError(
2268                "cp_model.new_interval_var: end must be 1-var affine or constant."
2269            )
2270        return IntervalVar(self.__model, start_expr, size_expr, end_expr, None, name)
2271
2272    def new_interval_var_series(
2273        self,
2274        name: str,
2275        index: pd.Index,
2276        starts: Union[LinearExprT, pd.Series],
2277        sizes: Union[LinearExprT, pd.Series],
2278        ends: Union[LinearExprT, pd.Series],
2279    ) -> pd.Series:
2280        """Creates a series of interval variables with the given name.
2281
2282        Args:
2283          name (str): Required. The name of the variable set.
2284          index (pd.Index): Required. The index to use for the variable set.
2285          starts (Union[LinearExprT, pd.Series]): The start of each interval in the
2286            set. If a `pd.Series` is passed in, it will be based on the
2287            corresponding values of the pd.Series.
2288          sizes (Union[LinearExprT, pd.Series]): The size of each interval in the
2289            set. If a `pd.Series` is passed in, it will be based on the
2290            corresponding values of the pd.Series.
2291          ends (Union[LinearExprT, pd.Series]): The ends of each interval in the
2292            set. If a `pd.Series` is passed in, it will be based on the
2293            corresponding values of the pd.Series.
2294
2295        Returns:
2296          pd.Series: The interval variable set indexed by its corresponding
2297          dimensions.
2298
2299        Raises:
2300          TypeError: if the `index` is invalid (e.g. a `DataFrame`).
2301          ValueError: if the `name` is not a valid identifier or already exists.
2302          ValueError: if the all the indexes do not match.
2303        """
2304        if not isinstance(index, pd.Index):
2305            raise TypeError("Non-index object is used as index")
2306        if not name.isidentifier():
2307            raise ValueError("name={} is not a valid identifier".format(name))
2308
2309        starts = _convert_to_linear_expr_series_and_validate_index(starts, index)
2310        sizes = _convert_to_linear_expr_series_and_validate_index(sizes, index)
2311        ends = _convert_to_linear_expr_series_and_validate_index(ends, index)
2312        interval_array = []
2313        for i in index:
2314            interval_array.append(
2315                self.new_interval_var(
2316                    start=starts[i],
2317                    size=sizes[i],
2318                    end=ends[i],
2319                    name=f"{name}[{i}]",
2320                )
2321            )
2322        return pd.Series(index=index, data=interval_array)
2323
2324    def new_fixed_size_interval_var(
2325        self, start: LinearExprT, size: IntegralT, name: str
2326    ) -> IntervalVar:
2327        """Creates an interval variable from start, and a fixed size.
2328
2329        An interval variable is a constraint, that is itself used in other
2330        constraints like NoOverlap.
2331
2332        Args:
2333          start: The start of the interval. It must be of the form a * var + b.
2334          size: The size of the interval. It must be an integer value.
2335          name: The name of the interval variable.
2336
2337        Returns:
2338          An `IntervalVar` object.
2339        """
2340        size = cmh.assert_is_int64(size)
2341        start_expr = self.parse_linear_expression(start)
2342        size_expr = self.parse_linear_expression(size)
2343        end_expr = self.parse_linear_expression(start + size)
2344        if len(start_expr.vars) > 1:
2345            raise TypeError(
2346                "cp_model.new_interval_var: start must be affine or constant."
2347            )
2348        return IntervalVar(self.__model, start_expr, size_expr, end_expr, None, name)
2349
2350    def new_fixed_size_interval_var_series(
2351        self,
2352        name: str,
2353        index: pd.Index,
2354        starts: Union[LinearExprT, pd.Series],
2355        sizes: Union[IntegralT, pd.Series],
2356    ) -> pd.Series:
2357        """Creates a series of interval variables with the given name.
2358
2359        Args:
2360          name (str): Required. The name of the variable set.
2361          index (pd.Index): Required. The index to use for the variable set.
2362          starts (Union[LinearExprT, pd.Series]): The start of each interval in the
2363            set. If a `pd.Series` is passed in, it will be based on the
2364            corresponding values of the pd.Series.
2365          sizes (Union[IntegralT, pd.Series]): The fixed size of each interval in
2366            the set. If a `pd.Series` is passed in, it will be based on the
2367            corresponding values of the pd.Series.
2368
2369        Returns:
2370          pd.Series: The interval variable set indexed by its corresponding
2371          dimensions.
2372
2373        Raises:
2374          TypeError: if the `index` is invalid (e.g. a `DataFrame`).
2375          ValueError: if the `name` is not a valid identifier or already exists.
2376          ValueError: if the all the indexes do not match.
2377        """
2378        if not isinstance(index, pd.Index):
2379            raise TypeError("Non-index object is used as index")
2380        if not name.isidentifier():
2381            raise ValueError("name={} is not a valid identifier".format(name))
2382
2383        starts = _convert_to_linear_expr_series_and_validate_index(starts, index)
2384        sizes = _convert_to_integral_series_and_validate_index(sizes, index)
2385        interval_array = []
2386        for i in index:
2387            interval_array.append(
2388                self.new_fixed_size_interval_var(
2389                    start=starts[i],
2390                    size=sizes[i],
2391                    name=f"{name}[{i}]",
2392                )
2393            )
2394        return pd.Series(index=index, data=interval_array)
2395
2396    def new_optional_interval_var(
2397        self,
2398        start: LinearExprT,
2399        size: LinearExprT,
2400        end: LinearExprT,
2401        is_present: LiteralT,
2402        name: str,
2403    ) -> IntervalVar:
2404        """Creates an optional interval var from start, size, end, and is_present.
2405
2406        An optional interval variable is a constraint, that is itself used in other
2407        constraints like NoOverlap. This constraint is protected by a presence
2408        literal that indicates if it is active or not.
2409
2410        Internally, it ensures that `is_present` implies `start + size ==
2411        end`.
2412
2413        Args:
2414          start: The start of the interval. It must be of the form a * var + b.
2415          size: The size of the interval. It must be of the form a * var + b.
2416          end: The end of the interval. It must be of the form a * var + b.
2417          is_present: A literal that indicates if the interval is active or not. A
2418            inactive interval is simply ignored by all constraints.
2419          name: The name of the interval variable.
2420
2421        Returns:
2422          An `IntervalVar` object.
2423        """
2424
2425        # Creates the IntervalConstraintProto object.
2426        is_present_index = self.get_or_make_boolean_index(is_present)
2427        start_expr = self.parse_linear_expression(start)
2428        size_expr = self.parse_linear_expression(size)
2429        end_expr = self.parse_linear_expression(end)
2430        if len(start_expr.vars) > 1:
2431            raise TypeError(
2432                "cp_model.new_interval_var: start must be affine or constant."
2433            )
2434        if len(size_expr.vars) > 1:
2435            raise TypeError(
2436                "cp_model.new_interval_var: size must be affine or constant."
2437            )
2438        if len(end_expr.vars) > 1:
2439            raise TypeError(
2440                "cp_model.new_interval_var: end must be affine or constant."
2441            )
2442        return IntervalVar(
2443            self.__model, start_expr, size_expr, end_expr, is_present_index, name
2444        )
2445
2446    def new_optional_interval_var_series(
2447        self,
2448        name: str,
2449        index: pd.Index,
2450        starts: Union[LinearExprT, pd.Series],
2451        sizes: Union[LinearExprT, pd.Series],
2452        ends: Union[LinearExprT, pd.Series],
2453        are_present: Union[LiteralT, pd.Series],
2454    ) -> pd.Series:
2455        """Creates a series of interval variables with the given name.
2456
2457        Args:
2458          name (str): Required. The name of the variable set.
2459          index (pd.Index): Required. The index to use for the variable set.
2460          starts (Union[LinearExprT, pd.Series]): The start of each interval in the
2461            set. If a `pd.Series` is passed in, it will be based on the
2462            corresponding values of the pd.Series.
2463          sizes (Union[LinearExprT, pd.Series]): The size of each interval in the
2464            set. If a `pd.Series` is passed in, it will be based on the
2465            corresponding values of the pd.Series.
2466          ends (Union[LinearExprT, pd.Series]): The ends of each interval in the
2467            set. If a `pd.Series` is passed in, it will be based on the
2468            corresponding values of the pd.Series.
2469          are_present (Union[LiteralT, pd.Series]): The performed literal of each
2470            interval in the set. If a `pd.Series` is passed in, it will be based on
2471            the corresponding values of the pd.Series.
2472
2473        Returns:
2474          pd.Series: The interval variable set indexed by its corresponding
2475          dimensions.
2476
2477        Raises:
2478          TypeError: if the `index` is invalid (e.g. a `DataFrame`).
2479          ValueError: if the `name` is not a valid identifier or already exists.
2480          ValueError: if the all the indexes do not match.
2481        """
2482        if not isinstance(index, pd.Index):
2483            raise TypeError("Non-index object is used as index")
2484        if not name.isidentifier():
2485            raise ValueError("name={} is not a valid identifier".format(name))
2486
2487        starts = _convert_to_linear_expr_series_and_validate_index(starts, index)
2488        sizes = _convert_to_linear_expr_series_and_validate_index(sizes, index)
2489        ends = _convert_to_linear_expr_series_and_validate_index(ends, index)
2490        are_present = _convert_to_literal_series_and_validate_index(are_present, index)
2491
2492        interval_array = []
2493        for i in index:
2494            interval_array.append(
2495                self.new_optional_interval_var(
2496                    start=starts[i],
2497                    size=sizes[i],
2498                    end=ends[i],
2499                    is_present=are_present[i],
2500                    name=f"{name}[{i}]",
2501                )
2502            )
2503        return pd.Series(index=index, data=interval_array)
2504

2506        self,
2507        start: LinearExprT,
2508        size: IntegralT,
2509        is_present: LiteralT,
2510        name: str,
2511    ) -> IntervalVar:

2521            inactive interval is simply ignored by all constraints.

2597    def add_no_overlap(self, interval_vars: Iterable[IntervalVar]) -> Constraint:
2598        """Adds NoOverlap(interval_vars).
2599
2600        A NoOverlap constraint ensures that all present intervals do not overlap
2601        in time.
2602
2603        Args:
2604          interval_vars: The list of interval variables to constrain.
2605
2606        Returns:
2607          An instance of the `Constraint` class.
2608        """
2609        ct = Constraint(self)
2610        model_ct = self.__model.constraints[ct.index]
2611        model_ct.no_overlap.intervals.extend(
2612            [self.get_interval_index(x) for x in interval_vars]
2613        )
2614        return ct
2615
2616    def add_no_overlap_2d(
2617        self,
2618        x_intervals: Iterable[IntervalVar],
2619        y_intervals: Iterable[IntervalVar],
2620    ) -> Constraint:
2621        """Adds NoOverlap2D(x_intervals, y_intervals).
2622
2623        A NoOverlap2D constraint ensures that all present rectangles do not overlap
2624        on a plane. Each rectangle is aligned with the X and Y axis, and is defined
2625        by two intervals which represent its projection onto the X and Y axis.
2626
2627        Furthermore, one box is optional if at least one of the x or y interval is
2628        optional.
2629
2630        Args:
2631          x_intervals: The X coordinates of the rectangles.
2632          y_intervals: The Y coordinates of the rectangles.
2633
2634        Returns:
2635          An instance of the `Constraint` class.
2636        """
2637        ct = Constraint(self)
2638        model_ct = self.__model.constraints[ct.index]
2639        model_ct.no_overlap_2d.x_intervals.extend(
2640            [self.get_interval_index(x) for x in x_intervals]
2641        )
2642        model_ct.no_overlap_2d.y_intervals.extend(
2643            [self.get_interval_index(x) for x in y_intervals]
2644        )
2645        return ct
2646
2647    def add_cumulative(
2648        self,
2649        intervals: Iterable[IntervalVar],
2650        demands: Iterable[LinearExprT],
2651        capacity: LinearExprT,
2652    ) -> Constraint:
2653        """Adds Cumulative(intervals, demands, capacity).
2654
2655        This constraint enforces that:
2656
2657            for all t:
2658              sum(demands[i]
2659                if (start(intervals[i]) <= t < end(intervals[i])) and
2660                (intervals[i] is present)) <= capacity
2661
2662        Args:
2663          intervals: The list of intervals.
2664          demands: The list of demands for each interval. Each demand must be >= 0.
2665            Each demand can be a 1-var affine expression (a * x + b).
2666          capacity: The maximum capacity of the cumulative constraint. It can be a
2667            1-var affine expression (a * x + b).
2668
2669        Returns:
2670          An instance of the `Constraint` class.
2671        """
2672        cumulative = Constraint(self)
2673        model_ct = self.__model.constraints[cumulative.index]
2674        model_ct.cumulative.intervals.extend(
2675            [self.get_interval_index(x) for x in intervals]
2676        )
2677        for d in demands:
2678            model_ct.cumulative.demands.append(self.parse_linear_expression(d))
2679        model_ct.cumulative.capacity.CopyFrom(self.parse_linear_expression(capacity))
2680        return cumulative
2681
2682    # Support for model cloning.
2683    def clone(self) -> "CpModel":
2684        """Reset the model, and creates a new one from a CpModelProto instance."""
2685        clone = CpModel()
2686        clone.proto.CopyFrom(self.proto)
2687        clone.rebuild_constant_map()
2688        return clone
2689
2690    def rebuild_constant_map(self):
2691        """Internal method used during model cloning."""
2692        for i, var in enumerate(self.__model.variables):
2693            if len(var.domain) == 2 and var.domain[0] == var.domain[1]:
2694                self.__constant_map[var.domain[0]] = i
2695
2696    def get_bool_var_from_proto_index(self, index: int) -> IntVar:
2697        """Returns an already created Boolean variable from its index."""
2698        if index < 0 or index >= len(self.__model.variables):
2699            raise ValueError(
2700                f"get_bool_var_from_proto_index: out of bound index {index}"
2701            )
2702        var = self.__model.variables[index]
2703        if len(var.domain) != 2 or var.domain[0] < 0 or var.domain[1] > 1:
2704            raise ValueError(
2705                f"get_bool_var_from_proto_index: index {index} does not reference"
2706                + " a Boolean variable"
2707            )
2708
2709        return IntVar(self.__model, index, None)
2710
2711    def get_int_var_from_proto_index(self, index: int) -> IntVar:
2712        """Returns an already created integer variable from its index."""
2713        if index < 0 or index >= len(self.__model.variables):
2714            raise ValueError(
2715                f"get_int_var_from_proto_index: out of bound index {index}"
2716            )
2717        return IntVar(self.__model, index, None)
2718
2719    def get_interval_var_from_proto_index(self, index: int) -> IntervalVar:
2720        """Returns an already created interval variable from its index."""
2721        if index < 0 or index >= len(self.__model.constraints):
2722            raise ValueError(
2723                f"get_interval_var_from_proto_index: out of bound index {index}"
2724            )
2725        ct = self.__model.constraints[index]
2726        if not ct.HasField("interval"):
2727            raise ValueError(
2728                f"get_interval_var_from_proto_index: index {index} does not"
2729                " reference an" + " interval variable"
2730            )
2731
2732        return IntervalVar(self.__model, index, None, None, None, None)
2733
2734    # Helpers.
2735
2736    def __str__(self):
2737        return str(self.__model)
2738
2739    @property
2740    def proto(self) -> cp_model_pb2.CpModelProto:
2741        """Returns the underlying CpModelProto."""
2742        return self.__model
2743
2744    def negated(self, index: int) -> int:
2745        return -index - 1
2746
2747    def get_or_make_index(self, arg: VariableT) -> int:
2748        """Returns the index of a variable, its negation, or a number."""
2749        if isinstance(arg, IntVar):
2750            return arg.index
2751        if (
2752            isinstance(arg, _ProductCst)
2753            and isinstance(arg.expression(), IntVar)
2754            and arg.coefficient() == -1
2755        ):
2756            return -arg.expression().index - 1
2757        if isinstance(arg, IntegralTypes):
2758            arg = cmh.assert_is_int64(arg)
2759            return self.get_or_make_index_from_constant(arg)
2760        raise TypeError("NotSupported: model.get_or_make_index(" + str(arg) + ")")
2761
2762    def get_or_make_boolean_index(self, arg: LiteralT) -> int:
2763        """Returns an index from a boolean expression."""
2764        if isinstance(arg, IntVar):
2765            self.assert_is_boolean_variable(arg)
2766            return arg.index
2767        if isinstance(arg, _NotBooleanVariable):
2768            self.assert_is_boolean_variable(arg.negated())
2769            return arg.index
2770        if isinstance(arg, IntegralTypes):
2771            arg = cmh.assert_is_zero_or_one(arg)
2772            return self.get_or_make_index_from_constant(arg)
2773        if cmh.is_boolean(arg):
2774            return self.get_or_make_index_from_constant(int(arg))
2775        raise TypeError(f"not supported: model.get_or_make_boolean_index({arg})")
2776
2777    def get_interval_index(self, arg: IntervalVar) -> int:
2778        if not isinstance(arg, IntervalVar):
2779            raise TypeError("NotSupported: model.get_interval_index(%s)" % arg)
2780        return arg.index
2781
2782    def get_or_make_index_from_constant(self, value: IntegralT) -> int:
2783        if value in self.__constant_map:
2784            return self.__constant_map[value]
2785        index = len(self.__model.variables)
2786        self.__model.variables.add(domain=[value, value])
2787        self.__constant_map[value] = index
2788        return index
2789
2790    def var_index_to_var_proto(
2791        self, var_index: int
2792    ) -> cp_model_pb2.IntegerVariableProto:
2793        if var_index >= 0:
2794            return self.__model.variables[var_index]
2795        else:
2796            return self.__model.variables[-var_index - 1]
2797
2798    def parse_linear_expression(
2799        self, linear_expr: LinearExprT, negate: bool = False
2800    ) -> cp_model_pb2.LinearExpressionProto:
2801        """Returns a LinearExpressionProto built from a LinearExpr instance."""
2802        result: cp_model_pb2.LinearExpressionProto = (
2803            cp_model_pb2.LinearExpressionProto()
2804        )
2805        mult = -1 if negate else 1
2806        if isinstance(linear_expr, IntegralTypes):
2807            result.offset = int(linear_expr) * mult
2808            return result
2809
2810        if isinstance(linear_expr, IntVar):
2811            result.vars.append(self.get_or_make_index(linear_expr))
2812            result.coeffs.append(mult)
2813            return result
2814
2815        coeffs_map, constant = cast(LinearExpr, linear_expr).get_integer_var_value_map()
2816        result.offset = constant * mult
2817        for t in coeffs_map.items():
2818            if not isinstance(t[0], IntVar):
2819                raise TypeError("Wrong argument" + str(t))
2820            c = cmh.assert_is_int64(t[1])
2821            result.vars.append(t[0].index)
2822            result.coeffs.append(c * mult)
2823        return result
2824
2825    def _set_objective(self, obj: ObjLinearExprT, minimize: bool):
2826        """Sets the objective of the model."""
2827        self.clear_objective()
2828        if isinstance(obj, IntVar):
2829            self.__model.objective.vars.append(obj.index)
2830            self.__model.objective.offset = 0
2831            if minimize:
2832                self.__model.objective.coeffs.append(1)
2833                self.__model.objective.scaling_factor = 1
2834            else:
2835                self.__model.objective.coeffs.append(-1)
2836                self.__model.objective.scaling_factor = -1
2837        elif isinstance(obj, LinearExpr):
2838            coeffs_map, constant, is_integer = obj.get_float_var_value_map()
2839            if is_integer:
2840                if minimize:
2841                    self.__model.objective.scaling_factor = 1
2842                    self.__model.objective.offset = constant
2843                else:
2844                    self.__model.objective.scaling_factor = -1
2845                    self.__model.objective.offset = -constant
2846                for v, c in coeffs_map.items():
2847                    c_as_int = int(c)
2848                    self.__model.objective.vars.append(v.index)
2849                    if minimize:
2850                        self.__model.objective.coeffs.append(c_as_int)
2851                    else:
2852                        self.__model.objective.coeffs.append(-c_as_int)
2853            else:
2854                self.__model.floating_point_objective.maximize = not minimize
2855                self.__model.floating_point_objective.offset = constant
2856                for v, c in coeffs_map.items():
2857                    self.__model.floating_point_objective.coeffs.append(c)
2858                    self.__model.floating_point_objective.vars.append(v.index)
2859        elif isinstance(obj, IntegralTypes):
2860            self.__model.objective.offset = int(obj)
2861            self.__model.objective.scaling_factor = 1
2862        else:
2863            raise TypeError("TypeError: " + str(obj) + " is not a valid objective")
2864
2865    def minimize(self, obj: ObjLinearExprT):
2866        """Sets the objective of the model to minimize(obj)."""
2867        self._set_objective(obj, minimize=True)
2868
2869    def maximize(self, obj: ObjLinearExprT):
2870        """Sets the objective of the model to maximize(obj)."""
2871        self._set_objective(obj, minimize=False)
2872
2873    def has_objective(self) -> bool:
2874        return self.__model.HasField("objective") or self.__model.HasField(
2875            "floating_point_objective"
2876        )
2877
2878    def clear_objective(self):
2879        self.__model.ClearField("objective")
2880        self.__model.ClearField("floating_point_objective")
2881
2882    def add_decision_strategy(
2883        self,
2884        variables: Sequence[IntVar],
2885        var_strategy: cp_model_pb2.DecisionStrategyProto.VariableSelectionStrategy,
2886        domain_strategy: cp_model_pb2.DecisionStrategyProto.DomainReductionStrategy,
2887    ) -> None:
2888        """Adds a search strategy to the model.
2889
2890        Args:
2891          variables: a list of variables this strategy will assign.
2892          var_strategy: heuristic to choose the next variable to assign.
2893          domain_strategy: heuristic to reduce the domain of the selected variable.
2894            Currently, this is advanced code: the union of all strategies added to
2895            the model must be complete, i.e. instantiates all variables. Otherwise,
2896            solve() will fail.
2897        """
2898
2899        strategy: cp_model_pb2.DecisionStrategyProto = (
2900            self.__model.search_strategy.add()
2901        )
2902        for v in variables:
2903            expr = strategy.exprs.add()
2904            if v.index >= 0:
2905                expr.vars.append(v.index)
2906                expr.coeffs.append(1)
2907            else:
2908                expr.vars.append(self.negated(v.index))
2909                expr.coeffs.append(-1)
2910                expr.offset = 1
2911
2912        strategy.variable_selection_strategy = var_strategy
2913        strategy.domain_reduction_strategy = domain_strategy
2914
2915    def model_stats(self) -> str:
2916        """Returns a string containing some model statistics."""
2917        return swig_helper.CpSatHelper.model_stats(self.__model)
2918
2919    def validate(self) -> str:
2920        """Returns a string indicating that the model is invalid."""
2921        return swig_helper.CpSatHelper.validate_model(self.__model)
2922
2923    def export_to_file(self, file: str) -> bool:
2924        """Write the model as a protocol buffer to 'file'.
2925
2926        Args:
2927          file: file to write the model to. If the filename ends with 'txt', the
2928            model will be written as a text file, otherwise, the binary format will
2929            be used.
2930
2931        Returns:
2932          True if the model was correctly written.
2933        """
2934        return swig_helper.CpSatHelper.write_model_to_file(self.__model, file)
2935
2936    def add_hint(self, var: IntVar, value: int) -> None:
2937        """Adds 'var == value' as a hint to the solver."""
2938        self.__model.solution_hint.vars.append(self.get_or_make_index(var))
2939        self.__model.solution_hint.values.append(value)

2946        """Adds the literal to the model as assumptions."""
2947        self.__model.assumptions.append(self.get_or_make_boolean_index(lit))

2949    def add_assumptions(self, literals: Iterable[LiteralT]) -> None:
2950        """Adds the literals to the model as assumptions."""
2951        for lit in literals:

2958    # Helpers.
2959    def assert_is_boolean_variable(self, x: LiteralT) -> None:
2960        if isinstance(x, IntVar):
2961            var = self.__model.variables[x.index]
2962            if len(var.domain) != 2 or var.domain[0] < 0 or var.domain[1] > 1:
2963                raise TypeError("TypeError: " + str(x) + " is not a boolean variable")
2964        elif not isinstance(x, _NotBooleanVariable):
2965            raise TypeError("TypeError: " + str(x) + " is not a boolean variable")

3041
3042@overload
3043def expand_generator_or_tuple(
3044    args: Union[Tuple[LiteralT, ...], Iterable[LiteralT]]
3045) -> Union[Iterable[LiteralT], LiteralT]: ...
3046
3047
3048@overload
3049def expand_generator_or_tuple(
3050    args: Union[Tuple[LinearExprT, ...], Iterable[LinearExprT]]
3051) -> Union[Iterable[LinearExprT], LinearExprT]: ...
3052
3053
3054def expand_generator_or_tuple(args):
3055    if hasattr(args, "__len__"):  # Tuple
3056        if len(args) != 1:
3057            return args
3058        if isinstance(args[0], (NumberTypes, LinearExpr)):
3059            return args
3060    # Generator
3061    return args[0]
3062
3063
3064def evaluate_linear_expr(
3065    expression: LinearExprT, solution: cp_model_pb2.CpSolverResponse
3066) -> int:
3067    """Evaluate a linear expression against a solution."""
3068    if isinstance(expression, IntegralTypes):
3069        return int(expression)
3070    if not isinstance(expression, LinearExpr):
3071        raise TypeError("Cannot interpret %s as a linear expression." % expression)
3072
3073    value = 0
3074    to_process = [(expression, 1)]
3075    while to_process:
3076        expr, coeff = to_process.pop()
3077        if isinstance(expr, IntegralTypes):
3078            value += int(expr) * coeff
3079        elif isinstance(expr, _ProductCst):
3080            to_process.append((expr.expression(), coeff * expr.coefficient()))
3081        elif isinstance(expr, _Sum):
3082            to_process.append((expr.left(), coeff))
3083            to_process.append((expr.right(), coeff))
3084        elif isinstance(expr, _SumArray):
3085            for e in expr.expressions():
3086                to_process.append((e, coeff))
3087            value += expr.constant() * coeff
3088        elif isinstance(expr, _WeightedSum):
3089            for e, c in zip(expr.expressions(), expr.coefficients()):
3090                to_process.append((e, coeff * c))
3091            value += expr.constant() * coeff
3092        elif isinstance(expr, IntVar):
3093            value += coeff * solution.solution[expr.index]
3094        elif isinstance(expr, _NotBooleanVariable):
3095            value += coeff * (1 - solution.solution[expr.negated().index])
3096        else:
3097            raise TypeError(f"Cannot interpret {expr} as a linear expression.")
3098
3099    return value
3100
3101
3102def evaluate_boolean_expression(
3103    literal: LiteralT, solution: cp_model_pb2.CpSolverResponse
3104) -> bool:
3105    """Evaluate a boolean expression against a solution."""
3106    if isinstance(literal, IntegralTypes):
3107        return bool(literal)
3108    elif isinstance(literal, IntVar) or isinstance(literal, _NotBooleanVariable):
3109        index: int = cast(Union[IntVar, _NotBooleanVariable], literal).index
3110        if index >= 0:
3111            return bool(solution.solution[index])
3112        else:
3113            return not solution.solution[-index - 1]
3114    else:
3115        raise TypeError(f"Cannot interpret {literal} as a boolean expression.")
3116

3118class CpSolver:
3119    """Main solver class.
3120
3121    The purpose of this class is to search for a solution to the model provided
3122    to the solve() method.
3123
3124    Once solve() is called, this class allows inspecting the solution found
3125    with the value() and boolean_value() methods, as well as general statistics
3126    about the solve procedure.
3127    """
3128
3129    def __init__(self) -> None:
3130        self.__solution: Optional[cp_model_pb2.CpSolverResponse] = None
3131        self.parameters: sat_parameters_pb2.SatParameters = (
3132            sat_parameters_pb2.SatParameters()
3133        )
3134        self.log_callback: Optional[Callable[[str], None]] = None
3135        self.best_bound_callback: Optional[Callable[[float], None]] = None
3136        self.__solve_wrapper: Optional[swig_helper.SolveWrapper] = None
3137        self.__lock: threading.Lock = threading.Lock()
3138
3139    def solve(
3140        self,
3141        model: CpModel,
3142        solution_callback: Optional["CpSolverSolutionCallback"] = None,
3143    ) -> cp_model_pb2.CpSolverStatus:
3144        """Solves a problem and passes each solution to the callback if not null."""
3145        with self.__lock:
3146            self.__solve_wrapper = swig_helper.SolveWrapper()
3147
3148        self.__solve_wrapper.set_parameters(self.parameters)
3149        if solution_callback is not None:
3150            self.__solve_wrapper.add_solution_callback(solution_callback)
3151
3152        if self.log_callback is not None:
3153            self.__solve_wrapper.add_log_callback(self.log_callback)
3154
3155        if self.best_bound_callback is not None:
3156            self.__solve_wrapper.add_best_bound_callback(self.best_bound_callback)
3157
3158        solution: cp_model_pb2.CpSolverResponse = self.__solve_wrapper.solve(
3159            model.proto
3160        )
3161        self.__solution = solution
3162
3163        if solution_callback is not None:
3164            self.__solve_wrapper.clear_solution_callback(solution_callback)
3165
3166        with self.__lock:
3167            self.__solve_wrapper = None
3168
3169        return solution.status
3170
3171    def stop_search(self) -> None:
3172        """Stops the current search asynchronously."""
3173        with self.__lock:
3174            if self.__solve_wrapper:
3175                self.__solve_wrapper.stop_search()
3176
3177    def value(self, expression: LinearExprT) -> int:
3178        """Returns the value of a linear expression after solve."""
3179        return evaluate_linear_expr(expression, self._solution)
3180
3181    def values(self, variables: _IndexOrSeries) -> pd.Series:
3182        """Returns the values of the input variables.
3183
3184        If `variables` is a `pd.Index`, then the output will be indexed by the
3185        variables. If `variables` is a `pd.Series` indexed by the underlying
3186        dimensions, then the output will be indexed by the same underlying
3187        dimensions.
3188
3189        Args:
3190          variables (Union[pd.Index, pd.Series]): The set of variables from which to
3191            get the values.
3192
3193        Returns:
3194          pd.Series: The values of all variables in the set.
3195        """
3196        solution = self._solution
3197        return _attribute_series(
3198            func=lambda v: solution.solution[v.index],
3199            values=variables,
3200        )
3201
3202    def boolean_value(self, literal: LiteralT) -> bool:
3203        """Returns the boolean value of a literal after solve."""
3204        return evaluate_boolean_expression(literal, self._solution)
3205
3206    def boolean_values(self, variables: _IndexOrSeries) -> pd.Series:
3207        """Returns the values of the input variables.
3208
3209        If `variables` is a `pd.Index`, then the output will be indexed by the
3210        variables. If `variables` is a `pd.Series` indexed by the underlying
3211        dimensions, then the output will be indexed by the same underlying
3212        dimensions.
3213
3214        Args:
3215          variables (Union[pd.Index, pd.Series]): The set of variables from which to
3216            get the values.
3217
3218        Returns:
3219          pd.Series: The values of all variables in the set.
3220        """
3221        solution = self._solution
3222        return _attribute_series(
3223            func=lambda literal: evaluate_boolean_expression(literal, solution),
3224            values=variables,
3225        )

3371    def SearchForAllSolutions(
3372        self, model: CpModel, callback: "CpSolverSolutionCallback"
3373    ) -> cp_model_pb2.CpSolverStatus:
3374        """DEPRECATED Use solve() with the right parameter.
3375
3376        Search for all solutions of a satisfiability problem.
3377
3378        This method searches for all feasible solutions of a given model.
3379        Then it feeds the solution to the callback.
3380
3381        Note that the model cannot contain an objective.
3382
3383        Args:
3384          model: The model to solve.
3385          callback: The callback that will be called at each solution.
3386
3387        Returns:
3388          The status of the solve:
3389
3390          * *FEASIBLE* if some solutions have been found
3391          * *INFEASIBLE* if the solver has proved there are no solution
3392          * *OPTIMAL* if all solutions have been found
3393        """
3394        warnings.warn(
3395            "search_for_all_solutions is deprecated; use solve() with"
3396            + "enumerate_all_solutions = True.",
3397            DeprecationWarning,
3398        )
3399        if model.has_objective():
3400            raise TypeError(
3401                "Search for all solutions is only defined on satisfiability problems"
3402            )
3403        # Store old parameter.
3404        enumerate_all = self.parameters.enumerate_all_solutions
3405        self.parameters.enumerate_all_solutions = True
3406
3407        status: cp_model_pb2.CpSolverStatus = self.solve(model, callback)
3408
3409        # Restore parameter.
3410        self.parameters.enumerate_all_solutions = enumerate_all
3411        return status

3416
3417class CpSolverSolutionCallback(swig_helper.SolutionCallback):
3418    """Solution callback.
3419
3420    This class implements a callback that will be called at each new solution
3421    found during search.
3422
3423    The method on_solution_callback() will be called by the solver, and must be
3424    implemented. The current solution can be queried using the boolean_value()
3425    and value() methods.
3426
3427    These methods returns the same information as their counterpart in the
3428    `CpSolver` class.
3429    """
3430
3431    def __init__(self) -> None:
3432        swig_helper.SolutionCallback.__init__(self)
3433
3434    def OnSolutionCallback(self) -> None:
3435        """Proxy for the same method in snake case."""
3436        self.on_solution_callback()
3437
3438    def boolean_value(self, lit: LiteralT) -> bool:
3439        """Returns the boolean value of a boolean literal.
3440
3441        Args:
3442            lit: A boolean variable or its negation.
3443
3444        Returns:
3445            The Boolean value of the literal in the solution.
3446
3447        Raises:
3448            RuntimeError: if `lit` is not a boolean variable or its negation.
3449        """
3450        if not self.has_response():
3451            raise RuntimeError("solve() has not been called.")
3452        if isinstance(lit, IntegralTypes):
3453            return bool(lit)
3454        if isinstance(lit, IntVar) or isinstance(lit, _NotBooleanVariable):
3455            return self.SolutionBooleanValue(
3456                cast(Union[IntVar, _NotBooleanVariable], lit).index
3457            )
3458        if cmh.is_boolean(lit):
3459            return bool(lit)
3460        raise TypeError(f"Cannot interpret {lit} as a boolean expression.")
3461
3462    def value(self, expression: LinearExprT) -> int:
3463        """Evaluates an linear expression in the current solution.
3464
3465        Args:
3466            expression: a linear expression of the model.
3467
3468        Returns:
3469            An integer value equal to the evaluation of the linear expression
3470            against the current solution.
3471
3472        Raises:
3473            RuntimeError: if 'expression' is not a LinearExpr.
3474        """
3475        if not self.has_response():
3476            raise RuntimeError("solve() has not been called.")
3477
3478        value = 0
3479        to_process = [(expression, 1)]
3480        while to_process:
3481            expr, coeff = to_process.pop()
3482            if isinstance(expr, IntegralTypes):
3483                value += int(expr) * coeff
3484            elif isinstance(expr, _ProductCst):
3485                to_process.append((expr.expression(), coeff * expr.coefficient()))
3486            elif isinstance(expr, _Sum):
3487                to_process.append((expr.left(), coeff))
3488                to_process.append((expr.right(), coeff))
3489            elif isinstance(expr, _SumArray):
3490                for e in expr.expressions():
3491                    to_process.append((e, coeff))
3492                    value += expr.constant() * coeff
3493            elif isinstance(expr, _WeightedSum):
3494                for e, c in zip(expr.expressions(), expr.coefficients()):
3495                    to_process.append((e, coeff * c))
3496                value += expr.constant() * coeff
3497            elif isinstance(expr, IntVar):
3498                value += coeff * self.SolutionIntegerValue(expr.index)
3499            elif isinstance(expr, _NotBooleanVariable):
3500                value += coeff * (1 - self.SolutionIntegerValue(expr.negated().index))
3501            else:
3502                raise TypeError(
3503                    f"cannot interpret {expression} as a linear expression."
3504                )
3505
3506        return value
3507
3508    def has_response(self) -> bool:
3509        return self.HasResponse()
3510
3511    def stop_search(self) -> None:
3512        """Stops the current search asynchronously."""
3513        if not self.has_response():
3514            raise RuntimeError("solve() has not been called.")
3515        self.StopSearch()
3516
3517    @property
3518    def objective_value(self) -> float:
3519        """Returns the value of the objective after solve."""
3520        if not self.has_response():

3689    values: _IndexOrSeries,

3706def _convert_to_integral_series_and_validate_index(
3707    value_or_series: Union[IntegralT, pd.Series], index: pd.Index
3708) -> pd.Series:
3709    """Returns a pd.Series of the given index with the corresponding values.
3710
3711    Args:
3712      value_or_series: the values to be converted (if applicable).
3713      index: the index of the resulting pd.Series.
3714
3715    Returns:
3716      pd.Series: The set of values with the given index.
3717
3718    Raises:
3719      TypeError: If the type of `value_or_series` is not recognized.
3720      ValueError: If the index does not match.
3721    """
3722    if isinstance(value_or_series, IntegralTypes):
3723        result = pd.Series(data=value_or_series, index=index)
3724    elif isinstance(value_or_series, pd.Series):
3725        if value_or_series.index.equals(index):
3726            result = value_or_series
3727        else:
3728            raise ValueError("index does not match")
3729    else:
3730        raise TypeError("invalid type={}".format(type(value_or_series)))
3731    return result

class Domain(pybind11_builtins.pybind11_object):

We call domain any subset of Int64 = [kint64min, kint64max].

This class can be used to represent such set efficiently as a sorted and non-adjacent list of intervals. This is efficient as long as the size of such list stays reasonable.

In the comments below, the domain of *this will always be written 'D'. Note that all the functions are safe with respect to integer overflow.

Domain()

__init__(self: Domain, arg0: int, arg1: int) -> None

By default, Domain will be empty.

def all_values(unknown):

all_values() -> Domain

Returns the full domain Int64.

def from_values(unknown):

from_values(values: list[int]) -> Domain

Creates a domain from the union of an unsorted list of integer values. Input values may be repeated, with no consequence on the output

def from_intervals(unknown):

from_intervals(intervals: list[list[int]]) -> Domain

This method is available in Python, Java and .NET. It allows building a Domain object from a list of intervals (long[][] in Java and .NET, [[0, 2], [5, 5], [8, 10]] in python).

def from_flat_intervals(unknown):

from_flat_intervals(flat_intervals: list[int]) -> Domain

This method is available in Python, Java and .NET. It allows building a Domain object from a flattened list of intervals (long[] in Java and .NET, [0, 2, 5, 5, 8, 10] in python).

def addition_with(unknown):

addition_with(self: Domain, domain: Domain) -> Domain

Returns {x ∈ Int64, ∃ a ∈ D, ∃ b ∈ domain, x = a + b}.

def complement(unknown):

complement(self: Domain) -> Domain

Returns the set Int64 ∖ D.

def contains(unknown):

contains(self: Domain, value: int) -> bool

Returns true iff value is in Domain.

def flattened_intervals(unknown):

flattened_intervals(self: Domain) -> list[int]

This method returns the flattened list of interval bounds of the domain.

Thus the domain {0, 1, 2, 5, 8, 9, 10} will return [0, 2, 5, 5, 8, 10] (as a C++ std::vector, as a java or C# long[], as a python list of integers).

def intersection_with(unknown):

intersection_with(self: Domain, domain: Domain) -> Domain

Returns the intersection of D and domain.

def is_empty(unknown):

is_empty(self: Domain) -> bool

Returns true if this is the empty set.

def size(unknown):

size(self: Domain) -> int

Returns the number of elements in the domain. It is capped at kint64max

def max(unknown):

max(self: Domain) -> int

Returns the max value of the domain. The domain must not be empty.

def min(unknown):

min(self: Domain) -> int

Returns the min value of the domain. The domain must not be empty.

def negation(unknown):

negation(self: Domain) -> Domain

Returns {x ∈ Int64, ∃ e ∈ D, x = -e}.

Note in particular that if the negation of Int64 is not Int64 but Int64 \ {kint64min} !!

def union_with(unknown):

union_with(self: Domain, domain: Domain) -> Domain

Returns the union of D and domain.

def display_bounds(bounds: Sequence[int]) -> str: 
169def display_bounds(bounds: Sequence[int]) -> str:
170    """Displays a flattened list of intervals."""
171    out = ""
172    for i in range(0, len(bounds), 2):
173        if i != 0:
174            out += ", "
175        if bounds[i] == bounds[i + 1]:
176            out += str(bounds[i])
177        else:
178            out += str(bounds[i]) + ".." + str(bounds[i + 1])
179    return out

def short_name(model: ortools.sat.cp_model_pb2.CpModelProto, i: int) -> str: 
182def short_name(model: cp_model_pb2.CpModelProto, i: int) -> str:
183    """Returns a short name of an integer variable, or its negation."""
184    if i < 0:
185        return "not(%s)" % short_name(model, -i - 1)
186    v = model.variables[i]
187    if v.name:
188        return v.name
189    elif len(v.domain) == 2 and v.domain[0] == v.domain[1]:
190        return str(v.domain[0])
191    else:
192        return "[%s]" % display_bounds(v.domain)

Returns a short name of an integer variable, or its negation.

def short_expr_name( model: ortools.sat.cp_model_pb2.CpModelProto, e: ortools.sat.cp_model_pb2.LinearExpressionProto) -> str: 
195def short_expr_name(
196    model: cp_model_pb2.CpModelProto, e: cp_model_pb2.LinearExpressionProto
197) -> str:
198    """Pretty-print LinearExpressionProto instances."""
199    if not e.vars:
200        return str(e.offset)
201    if len(e.vars) == 1:
202        var_name = short_name(model, e.vars[0])
203        coeff = e.coeffs[0]
204        result = ""
205        if coeff == 1:
206            result = var_name
207        elif coeff == -1:
208            result = f"-{var_name}"
209        elif coeff != 0:
210            result = f"{coeff} * {var_name}"
211        if e.offset > 0:
212            result = f"{result} + {e.offset}"
213        elif e.offset < 0:
214            result = f"{result} - {-e.offset}"
215        return result
216    # TODO(user): Support more than affine expressions.
217    return str(e)

Pretty-print LinearExpressionProto instances.

class LinearExpr: 
220class LinearExpr:
221    """Holds an integer linear expression.
222
223    A linear expression is built from integer constants and variables.
224    For example, `x + 2 * (y - z + 1)`.
225
226    Linear expressions are used in CP-SAT models in constraints and in the
227    objective:
228
229    * You can define linear constraints as in:
230
231    ```
232    model.add(x + 2 * y <= 5)
233    model.add(sum(array_of_vars) == 5)
234    ```
235
236    * In CP-SAT, the objective is a linear expression:
237
238    ```
239    model.minimize(x + 2 * y + z)
240    ```
241
242    * For large arrays, using the LinearExpr class is faster that using the python
243    `sum()` function. You can create constraints and the objective from lists of
244    linear expressions or coefficients as follows:
245
246    ```
247    model.minimize(cp_model.LinearExpr.sum(expressions))
248    model.add(cp_model.LinearExpr.weighted_sum(expressions, coefficients) >= 0)
249    ```
250    """
251
252    @classmethod
253    def sum(cls, expressions: Sequence[LinearExprT]) -> LinearExprT:
254        """Creates the expression sum(expressions)."""
255        if len(expressions) == 1:
256            return expressions[0]
257        return _SumArray(expressions)
258
259    @overload
260    @classmethod
261    def weighted_sum(
262        cls,
263        expressions: Sequence[LinearExprT],
264        coefficients: Sequence[IntegralT],
265    ) -> LinearExprT: ...
266
267    @overload
268    @classmethod
269    def weighted_sum(
270        cls,
271        expressions: Sequence[ObjLinearExprT],
272        coefficients: Sequence[NumberT],
273    ) -> ObjLinearExprT: ...
274
275    @classmethod
276    def weighted_sum(cls, expressions, coefficients):
277        """Creates the expression sum(expressions[i] * coefficients[i])."""
278        if LinearExpr.is_empty_or_all_null(coefficients):
279            return 0
280        elif len(expressions) == 1:
281            return expressions[0] * coefficients[0]
282        else:
283            return _WeightedSum(expressions, coefficients)
284
285    @overload
286    @classmethod
287    def term(
288        cls,
289        expressions: LinearExprT,
290        coefficients: IntegralT,
291    ) -> LinearExprT: ...
292
293    @overload
294    @classmethod
295    def term(
296        cls,
297        expressions: ObjLinearExprT,
298        coefficients: NumberT,
299    ) -> ObjLinearExprT: ...
300
301    @classmethod
302    def term(cls, expression, coefficient):
303        """Creates `expression * coefficient`."""
304        if cmh.is_zero(coefficient):
305            return 0
306        else:
307            return expression * coefficient
308
309    @classmethod
310    def is_empty_or_all_null(cls, coefficients: Sequence[NumberT]) -> bool:
311        for c in coefficients:
312            if not cmh.is_zero(c):
313                return False
314        return True
315
316    @classmethod
317    def rebuild_from_linear_expression_proto(
318        cls,
319        model: cp_model_pb2.CpModelProto,
320        proto: cp_model_pb2.LinearExpressionProto,
321    ) -> LinearExprT:
322        """Recreate a LinearExpr from a LinearExpressionProto."""
323        offset = proto.offset
324        num_elements = len(proto.vars)
325        if num_elements == 0:
326            return offset
327        elif num_elements == 1:
328            return (
329                IntVar(model, proto.vars[0], None) * proto.coeffs[0] + offset
330            )  # pytype: disable=bad-return-type
331        else:
332            variables = []
333            coeffs = []
334            all_ones = True
335            for index, coeff in zip(proto.vars, proto.coeffs):
336                variables.append(IntVar(model, index, None))
337                coeffs.append(coeff)
338                if not cmh.is_one(coeff):
339                    all_ones = False
340            if all_ones:
341                return _SumArray(variables, offset)
342            else:
343                return _WeightedSum(variables, coeffs, offset)
344
345    def get_integer_var_value_map(self) -> Tuple[Dict["IntVar", int], int]:
346        """Scans the expression, and returns (var_coef_map, constant)."""
347        coeffs: Dict["IntVar", int] = collections.defaultdict(int)
348        constant = 0
349        to_process: List[Tuple[LinearExprT, int]] = [(self, 1)]
350        while to_process:  # Flatten to avoid recursion.
351            expr: LinearExprT
352            coeff: int
353            expr, coeff = to_process.pop()
354            if isinstance(expr, IntegralTypes):
355                constant += coeff * int(expr)
356            elif isinstance(expr, _ProductCst):
357                to_process.append((expr.expression(), coeff * expr.coefficient()))
358            elif isinstance(expr, _Sum):
359                to_process.append((expr.left(), coeff))
360                to_process.append((expr.right(), coeff))
361            elif isinstance(expr, _SumArray):
362                for e in expr.expressions():
363                    to_process.append((e, coeff))
364                constant += expr.constant() * coeff
365            elif isinstance(expr, _WeightedSum):
366                for e, c in zip(expr.expressions(), expr.coefficients()):
367                    to_process.append((e, coeff * c))
368                constant += expr.constant() * coeff
369            elif isinstance(expr, IntVar):
370                coeffs[expr] += coeff
371            elif isinstance(expr, _NotBooleanVariable):
372                constant += coeff
373                coeffs[expr.negated()] -= coeff
374            elif isinstance(expr, NumberTypes):
375                raise TypeError(
376                    f"Floating point constants are not supported in constraints: {expr}"
377                )
378            else:
379                raise TypeError("Unrecognized linear expression: " + str(expr))
380
381        return coeffs, constant
382
383    def get_float_var_value_map(
384        self,
385    ) -> Tuple[Dict["IntVar", float], float, bool]:
386        """Scans the expression. Returns (var_coef_map, constant, is_integer)."""
387        coeffs: Dict["IntVar", Union[int, float]] = {}
388        constant: Union[int, float] = 0
389        to_process: List[Tuple[LinearExprT, Union[int, float]]] = [(self, 1)]
390        while to_process:  # Flatten to avoid recursion.
391            expr, coeff = to_process.pop()
392            if isinstance(expr, IntegralTypes):  # Keep integrality.
393                constant += coeff * int(expr)
394            elif isinstance(expr, NumberTypes):
395                constant += coeff * float(expr)
396            elif isinstance(expr, _ProductCst):
397                to_process.append((expr.expression(), coeff * expr.coefficient()))
398            elif isinstance(expr, _Sum):
399                to_process.append((expr.left(), coeff))
400                to_process.append((expr.right(), coeff))
401            elif isinstance(expr, _SumArray):
402                for e in expr.expressions():
403                    to_process.append((e, coeff))
404                constant += expr.constant() * coeff
405            elif isinstance(expr, _WeightedSum):
406                for e, c in zip(expr.expressions(), expr.coefficients()):
407                    to_process.append((e, coeff * c))
408                constant += expr.constant() * coeff
409            elif isinstance(expr, IntVar):
410                if expr in coeffs:
411                    coeffs[expr] += coeff
412                else:
413                    coeffs[expr] = coeff
414            elif isinstance(expr, _NotBooleanVariable):
415                constant += coeff
416                if expr.negated() in coeffs:
417                    coeffs[expr.negated()] -= coeff
418                else:
419                    coeffs[expr.negated()] = -coeff
420            else:
421                raise TypeError("Unrecognized linear expression: " + str(expr))
422        is_integer = isinstance(constant, IntegralTypes)
423        if is_integer:
424            for coeff in coeffs.values():
425                if not isinstance(coeff, IntegralTypes):
426                    is_integer = False
427                    break
428        return coeffs, constant, is_integer
429
430    def __hash__(self) -> int:
431        return object.__hash__(self)
432
433    def __abs__(self) -> NoReturn:
434        raise NotImplementedError(
435            "calling abs() on a linear expression is not supported, "
436            "please use CpModel.add_abs_equality"
437        )
438
439    @overload
440    def __add__(self, arg: "LinearExpr") -> "LinearExpr": ...
441
442    @overload
443    def __add__(self, arg: NumberT) -> "LinearExpr": ...
444
445    def __add__(self, arg):
446        if cmh.is_zero(arg):
447            return self
448        return _Sum(self, arg)
449

465    def __sub__(self, arg):
466        if cmh.is_zero(arg):
467            return self
468        if isinstance(arg, NumberTypes):
469            arg = cmh.assert_is_a_number(arg)
470            return _Sum(self, -arg)
471        else:
472            return _Sum(self, -arg)

566    def __eq__(self, arg: LinearExprT) -> BoundedLinearExprT:  # type: ignore[override]
567        if arg is None:
568            return False
569        if isinstance(arg, IntegralTypes):
570            arg = cmh.assert_is_int64(arg)
571            return BoundedLinearExpression(self, [arg, arg])
572        elif isinstance(arg, LinearExpr):
573            return BoundedLinearExpression(self - arg, [0, 0])
574        else:
575            return False
576
577    def __ge__(self, arg: LinearExprT) -> "BoundedLinearExpression":
578        if isinstance(arg, IntegralTypes):
579            arg = cmh.assert_is_int64(arg)
580            return BoundedLinearExpression(self, [arg, INT_MAX])
581        else:
582            return BoundedLinearExpression(self - arg, [0, INT_MAX])
583
584    def __le__(self, arg: LinearExprT) -> "BoundedLinearExpression":
585        if isinstance(arg, IntegralTypes):
586            arg = cmh.assert_is_int64(arg)
587            return BoundedLinearExpression(self, [INT_MIN, arg])
588        else:
589            return BoundedLinearExpression(self - arg, [INT_MIN, 0])
590
591    def __lt__(self, arg: LinearExprT) -> "BoundedLinearExpression":
592        if isinstance(arg, IntegralTypes):
593            arg = cmh.assert_is_int64(arg)
594            if arg == INT_MIN:
595                raise ArithmeticError("< INT_MIN is not supported")
596            return BoundedLinearExpression(self, [INT_MIN, arg - 1])
597        else:
598            return BoundedLinearExpression(self - arg, [INT_MIN, -1])
599
600    def __gt__(self, arg: LinearExprT) -> "BoundedLinearExpression":
601        if isinstance(arg, IntegralTypes):
602            arg = cmh.assert_is_int64(arg)
603            if arg == INT_MAX:
604                raise ArithmeticError("> INT_MAX is not supported")
605            return BoundedLinearExpression(self, [arg + 1, INT_MAX])
606        else:
607            return BoundedLinearExpression(self - arg, [1, INT_MAX])
608
609    def __ne__(self, arg: LinearExprT) -> BoundedLinearExprT:  # type: ignore[override]
610        if arg is None:
611            return True
612        if isinstance(arg, IntegralTypes):
613            arg = cmh.assert_is_int64(arg)
614            if arg == INT_MAX:
615                return BoundedLinearExpression(self, [INT_MIN, INT_MAX - 1])
616            elif arg == INT_MIN:
617                return BoundedLinearExpression(self, [INT_MIN + 1, INT_MAX])
618            else:
619                return BoundedLinearExpression(
620                    self, [INT_MIN, arg - 1, arg + 1, INT_MAX]
621                )
622        elif isinstance(arg, LinearExpr):
623            return BoundedLinearExpression(self - arg, [INT_MIN, -1, 1, INT_MAX])
624        else:
625            return True
626
627    # Compatibility with pre PEP8
628    # pylint: disable=invalid-name

630    def Sum(cls, expressions: Sequence[LinearExprT]) -> LinearExprT:
631        """Creates the expression sum(expressions)."""
632        return cls.sum(expressions)

676    # pylint: enable=invalid-name

Holds an integer linear expression.

A linear expression is built from integer constants and variables. For example, x + 2 * (y - z + 1).

Linear expressions are used in CP-SAT models in constraints and in the objective:

  • You can define linear constraints as in:
model.add(x + 2 * y <= 5)
model.add(sum(array_of_vars) == 5)
  • In CP-SAT, the objective is a linear expression:
model.minimize(x + 2 * y + z)
  • For large arrays, using the LinearExpr class is faster that using the python sum() function. You can create constraints and the objective from lists of linear expressions or coefficients as follows:
model.minimize(cp_model.LinearExpr.sum(expressions))
model.add(cp_model.LinearExpr.weighted_sum(expressions, coefficients) >= 0)
@classmethod
def sum( cls, expressions: Sequence[Union[LinearExpr, IntVar, int, numpy.int8, numpy.uint8, numpy.int32, numpy.uint32, numpy.int64, numpy.uint64]]) -> Union[LinearExpr, IntVar, int, numpy.int8, numpy.uint8, numpy.int32, numpy.uint32, numpy.int64, numpy.uint64]: 
252    @classmethod
253    def sum(cls, expressions: Sequence[LinearExprT]) -> LinearExprT:
254        """Creates the expression sum(expressions)."""
255        if len(expressions) == 1:
256            return expressions[0]
257        return _SumArray(expressions)

@classmethod
def weighted_sum(cls, expressions, coefficients): 
275    @classmethod
276    def weighted_sum(cls, expressions, coefficients):
277        """Creates the expression sum(expressions[i] * coefficients[i])."""
278        if LinearExpr.is_empty_or_all_null(coefficients):
279            return 0
280        elif len(expressions) == 1:
281            return expressions[0] * coefficients[0]
282        else:
283            return _WeightedSum(expressions, coefficients)

@classmethod
def is_empty_or_all_null( cls, coefficients: Sequence[Union[int, float, numpy.int8, numpy.uint8, numpy.int32, numpy.uint32, numpy.int64, numpy.uint64, numpy.float64]]) -> bool: 
309    @classmethod
310    def is_empty_or_all_null(cls, coefficients: Sequence[NumberT]) -> bool:
311        for c in coefficients:
312            if not cmh.is_zero(c):
313                return False
314        return True
@classmethod
def rebuild_from_linear_expression_proto( cls, model: ortools.sat.cp_model_pb2.CpModelProto, proto: ortools.sat.cp_model_pb2.LinearExpressionProto) -> Union[LinearExpr, IntVar, int, numpy.int8, numpy.uint8, numpy.int32, numpy.uint32, numpy.int64, numpy.uint64]: 
316    @classmethod
317    def rebuild_from_linear_expression_proto(
318        cls,
319        model: cp_model_pb2.CpModelProto,
320        proto: cp_model_pb2.LinearExpressionProto,
321    ) -> LinearExprT:
322        """Recreate a LinearExpr from a LinearExpressionProto."""
323        offset = proto.offset
324        num_elements = len(proto.vars)
325        if num_elements == 0:
326            return offset
327        elif num_elements == 1:
328            return (
329                IntVar(model, proto.vars[0], None) * proto.coeffs[0] + offset
330            )  # pytype: disable=bad-return-type
331        else:
332            variables = []
333            coeffs = []
334            all_ones = True
335            for index, coeff in zip(proto.vars, proto.coeffs):
336                variables.append(IntVar(model, index, None))
337                coeffs.append(coeff)
338                if not cmh.is_one(coeff):
339                    all_ones = False
340            if all_ones:
341                return _SumArray(variables, offset)
342            else:
343                return _WeightedSum(variables, coeffs, offset)

Recreate a LinearExpr from a LinearExpressionProto.

def get_integer_var_value_map(self) -> Tuple[Dict[IntVar, int], int]: 
345    def get_integer_var_value_map(self) -> Tuple[Dict["IntVar", int], int]:
346        """Scans the expression, and returns (var_coef_map, constant)."""
347        coeffs: Dict["IntVar", int] = collections.defaultdict(int)
348        constant = 0
349        to_process: List[Tuple[LinearExprT, int]] = [(self, 1)]
350        while to_process:  # Flatten to avoid recursion.
351            expr: LinearExprT
352            coeff: int
353            expr, coeff = to_process.pop()
354            if isinstance(expr, IntegralTypes):
355                constant += coeff * int(expr)
356            elif isinstance(expr, _ProductCst):
357                to_process.append((expr.expression(), coeff * expr.coefficient()))
358            elif isinstance(expr, _Sum):
359                to_process.append((expr.left(), coeff))
360                to_process.append((expr.right(), coeff))
361            elif isinstance(expr, _SumArray):
362                for e in expr.expressions():
363                    to_process.append((e, coeff))
364                constant += expr.constant() * coeff
365            elif isinstance(expr, _WeightedSum):
366                for e, c in zip(expr.expressions(), expr.coefficients()):
367                    to_process.append((e, coeff * c))
368                constant += expr.constant() * coeff
369            elif isinstance(expr, IntVar):
370                coeffs[expr] += coeff
371            elif isinstance(expr, _NotBooleanVariable):
372                constant += coeff
373                coeffs[expr.negated()] -= coeff
374            elif isinstance(expr, NumberTypes):
375                raise TypeError(
376                    f"Floating point constants are not supported in constraints: {expr}"
377                )
378            else:
379                raise TypeError("Unrecognized linear expression: " + str(expr))
380
381        return coeffs, constant

Scans the expression, and returns (var_coef_map, constant).

class IntVar(LinearExpr): 
833class IntVar(LinearExpr):
834    """An integer variable.
835
836    An IntVar is an object that can take on any integer value within defined
837    ranges. Variables appear in constraint like:
838
839        x + y >= 5
840        AllDifferent([x, y, z])
841
842    Solving a model is equivalent to finding, for each variable, a single value
843    from the set of initial values (called the initial domain), such that the
844    model is feasible, or optimal if you provided an objective function.
845    """
846
847    def __init__(
848        self,
849        model: cp_model_pb2.CpModelProto,
850        domain: Union[int, sorted_interval_list.Domain],
851        name: Optional[str],
852    ) -> None:
853        """See CpModel.new_int_var below."""
854        self.__index: int
855        self.__var: cp_model_pb2.IntegerVariableProto
856        self.__negation: Optional[_NotBooleanVariable] = None
857        # Python do not support multiple __init__ methods.
858        # This method is only called from the CpModel class.
859        # We hack the parameter to support the two cases:
860        # case 1:
861        #     model is a CpModelProto, domain is a Domain, and name is a string.
862        # case 2:
863        #     model is a CpModelProto, domain is an index (int), and name is None.
864        if isinstance(domain, IntegralTypes) and name is None:
865            self.__index = int(domain)
866            self.__var = model.variables[domain]
867        else:
868            self.__index = len(model.variables)
869            self.__var = model.variables.add()
870            self.__var.domain.extend(
871                cast(sorted_interval_list.Domain, domain).flattened_intervals()
872            )
873            if name is not None:
874                self.__var.name = name
875
876    @property
877    def index(self) -> int:
878        """Returns the index of the variable in the model."""
879        return self.__index
880
881    @property
882    def proto(self) -> cp_model_pb2.IntegerVariableProto:
883        """Returns the variable protobuf."""
884        return self.__var
885
886    def is_equal_to(self, other: Any) -> bool:
887        """Returns true if self == other in the python sense."""
888        if not isinstance(other, IntVar):
889            return False
890        return self.index == other.index
891
892    def __str__(self) -> str:
893        if not self.__var.name:
894            if (
895                len(self.__var.domain) == 2
896                and self.__var.domain[0] == self.__var.domain[1]
897            ):
898                # Special case for constants.
899                return str(self.__var.domain[0])
900            else:
901                return "unnamed_var_%i" % self.__index
902        return self.__var.name
903
904    def __repr__(self) -> str:
905        return "%s(%s)" % (self.__var.name, display_bounds(self.__var.domain))
906
907    @property
908    def name(self) -> str:
909        if not self.__var or not self.__var.name:
910            return ""
911        return self.__var.name
912
913    def negated(self) -> "_NotBooleanVariable":
914        """Returns the negation of a Boolean variable.
915
916        This method implements the logical negation of a Boolean variable.
917        It is only valid if the variable has a Boolean domain (0 or 1).
918
919        Note that this method is nilpotent: `x.negated().negated() == x`.
920        """
921
922        for bound in self.__var.domain:
923            if bound < 0 or bound > 1:
924                raise TypeError(
925                    f"cannot call negated on a non boolean variable: {self}"
926                )
927        if self.__negation is None:
928            self.__negation = _NotBooleanVariable(self)
929        return self.__negation
930
931    def __invert__(self) -> "_NotBooleanVariable":
932        """Returns the logical negation of a Boolean variable."""
933        return self.negated()
934
935    # Pre PEP8 compatibility.
936    # pylint: disable=invalid-name
937    Not = negated
938
939    def Name(self) -> str:
940        return self.name
941
942    def Proto(self) -> cp_model_pb2.IntegerVariableProto:
943        return self.proto
944
945    def Index(self) -> int:
946        return self.index

def negated(self) -> ortools.sat.python.cp_model._NotBooleanVariable: 
913    def negated(self) -> "_NotBooleanVariable":
914        """Returns the negation of a Boolean variable.
915
916        This method implements the logical negation of a Boolean variable.
917        It is only valid if the variable has a Boolean domain (0 or 1).
918
919        Note that this method is nilpotent: `x.negated().negated() == x`.
920        """
921
922        for bound in self.__var.domain:
923            if bound < 0 or bound > 1:
924                raise TypeError(
925                    f"cannot call negated on a non boolean variable: {self}"
926                )
927        if self.__negation is None:
928            self.__negation = _NotBooleanVariable(self)
929        return self.__negation

class BoundedLinearExpression: 
 991class BoundedLinearExpression:
 992    """Represents a linear constraint: `lb <= linear expression <= ub`.
 993
 994    The only use of this class is to be added to the CpModel through
 995    `CpModel.add(expression)`, as in:
 996
 997        model.add(x + 2 * y -1 >= z)
 998    """
 999
1000    def __init__(self, expr: LinearExprT, bounds: Sequence[int]) -> None:
1001        self.__expr: LinearExprT = expr
1002        self.__bounds: Sequence[int] = bounds
1003
1004    def __str__(self):
1005        if len(self.__bounds) == 2:
1006            lb, ub = self.__bounds
1007            if lb > INT_MIN and ub < INT_MAX:
1008                if lb == ub:
1009                    return str(self.__expr) + " == " + str(lb)
1010                else:
1011                    return str(lb) + " <= " + str(self.__expr) + " <= " + str(ub)
1012            elif lb > INT_MIN:
1013                return str(self.__expr) + " >= " + str(lb)
1014            elif ub < INT_MAX:
1015                return str(self.__expr) + " <= " + str(ub)
1016            else:
1017                return "True (unbounded expr " + str(self.__expr) + ")"
1018        elif (
1019            len(self.__bounds) == 4
1020            and self.__bounds[0] == INT_MIN
1021            and self.__bounds[1] + 2 == self.__bounds[2]
1022            and self.__bounds[3] == INT_MAX
1023        ):
1024            return str(self.__expr) + " != " + str(self.__bounds[1] + 1)
1025        else:
1026            return str(self.__expr) + " in [" + display_bounds(self.__bounds) + "]"
1027
1028    def expression(self) -> LinearExprT:
1029        return self.__expr
1030
1031    def bounds(self) -> Sequence[int]:
1032        return self.__bounds
1033
1034    def __bool__(self) -> bool:
1035        expr = self.__expr
1036        if isinstance(expr, LinearExpr):
1037            coeffs_map, constant = expr.get_integer_var_value_map()
1038            all_coeffs = set(coeffs_map.values())
1039            same_var = set([0])
1040            eq_bounds = [0, 0]
1041            different_vars = set([-1, 1])
1042            ne_bounds = [INT_MIN, -1, 1, INT_MAX]
1043            if (
1044                len(coeffs_map) == 1
1045                and all_coeffs == same_var
1046                and constant == 0
1047                and (self.__bounds == eq_bounds or self.__bounds == ne_bounds)
1048            ):
1049                return self.__bounds == eq_bounds
1050            if (
1051                len(coeffs_map) == 2
1052                and all_coeffs == different_vars
1053                and constant == 0
1054                and (self.__bounds == eq_bounds or self.__bounds == ne_bounds)
1055            ):
1056                return self.__bounds == ne_bounds
1057
1058        raise NotImplementedError(
1059            f'Evaluating a BoundedLinearExpression "{self}" as a Boolean value'
1060            + " is not supported."
1061        )

class Constraint: 
1064class Constraint:
1065    """Base class for constraints.
1066
1067    Constraints are built by the CpModel through the add<XXX> methods.
1068    Once created by the CpModel class, they are automatically added to the model.
1069    The purpose of this class is to allow specification of enforcement literals
1070    for this constraint.
1071
1072        b = model.new_bool_var('b')
1073        x = model.new_int_var(0, 10, 'x')
1074        y = model.new_int_var(0, 10, 'y')
1075
1076        model.add(x + 2 * y == 5).only_enforce_if(b.negated())
1077    """
1078
1079    def __init__(
1080        self,
1081        cp_model: "CpModel",
1082    ) -> None:
1083        self.__index: int = len(cp_model.proto.constraints)
1084        self.__cp_model: "CpModel" = cp_model
1085        self.__constraint: cp_model_pb2.ConstraintProto = (
1086            cp_model.proto.constraints.add()
1087        )
1088
1089    @overload
1090    def only_enforce_if(self, boolvar: Iterable[LiteralT]) -> "Constraint": ...
1091
1092    @overload
1093    def only_enforce_if(self, *boolvar: LiteralT) -> "Constraint": ...
1094
1095    def only_enforce_if(self, *boolvar) -> "Constraint":
1096        """Adds an enforcement literal to the constraint.
1097
1098        This method adds one or more literals (that is, a boolean variable or its
1099        negation) as enforcement literals. The conjunction of all these literals
1100        determines whether the constraint is active or not. It acts as an
1101        implication, so if the conjunction is true, it implies that the constraint
1102        must be enforced. If it is false, then the constraint is ignored.
1103
1104        BoolOr, BoolAnd, and linear constraints all support enforcement literals.
1105
1106        Args:
1107          *boolvar: One or more Boolean literals.
1108
1109        Returns:
1110          self.
1111        """
1112        for lit in expand_generator_or_tuple(boolvar):
1113            if (cmh.is_boolean(lit) and lit) or (
1114                isinstance(lit, IntegralTypes) and lit == 1
1115            ):
1116                # Always true. Do nothing.
1117                pass
1118            elif (cmh.is_boolean(lit) and not lit) or (
1119                isinstance(lit, IntegralTypes) and lit == 0
1120            ):
1121                self.__constraint.enforcement_literal.append(
1122                    self.__cp_model.new_constant(0).index
1123                )
1124            else:
1125                self.__constraint.enforcement_literal.append(
1126                    cast(Union[IntVar, _NotBooleanVariable], lit).index
1127                )
1128        return self
1129
1130    def with_name(self, name: str) -> "Constraint":
1131        """Sets the name of the constraint."""
1132        if name:
1133            self.__constraint.name = name
1134        else:
1135            self.__constraint.ClearField("name")
1136        return self
1137
1138    @property
1139    def name(self) -> str:
1140        """Returns the name of the constraint."""
1141        if not self.__constraint or not self.__constraint.name:
1142            return ""
1143        return self.__constraint.name
1144
1145    @property
1146    def index(self) -> int:
1147        """Returns the index of the constraint in the model."""
1148        return self.__index
1149
1150    @property
1151    def proto(self) -> cp_model_pb2.ConstraintProto:
1152        """Returns the constraint protobuf."""
1153        return self.__constraint
1154
1155    # Pre PEP8 compatibility.
1156    # pylint: disable=invalid-name
1157    OnlyEnforceIf = only_enforce_if
1158    WithName = with_name
1159
1160    def Name(self) -> str:
1161        return self.name
1162
1163    def Index(self) -> int:
1164        return self.index

1166    def Proto(self) -> cp_model_pb2.ConstraintProto:
1167        return self.proto
