class IntervalVar: 
1172class IntervalVar:
1173    """Represents an Interval variable.
1174
1175    An interval variable is both a constraint and a variable. It is defined by
1176    three integer variables: start, size, and end.
1177
1178    It is a constraint because, internally, it enforces that start + size == end.
1179
1180    It is also a variable as it can appear in specific scheduling constraints:
1181    NoOverlap, NoOverlap2D, Cumulative.
1182
1183    Optionally, an enforcement literal can be added to this constraint, in which
1184    case these scheduling constraints will ignore interval variables with
1185    enforcement literals assigned to false. Conversely, these constraints will
1186    also set these enforcement literals to false if they cannot fit these
1187    intervals into the schedule.
1188
1189    Raises:
1190      ValueError: if start, size, end are not defined, or have the wrong type.
1191    """
1192
1193    def __init__(
1194        self,
1195        model: cp_model_pb2.CpModelProto,
1196        start: Union[cp_model_pb2.LinearExpressionProto, int],
1197        size: Optional[cp_model_pb2.LinearExpressionProto],
1198        end: Optional[cp_model_pb2.LinearExpressionProto],
1199        is_present_index: Optional[int],
1200        name: Optional[str],
1201    ) -> None:
1202        self.__model: cp_model_pb2.CpModelProto = model
1203        self.__index: int
1204        self.__ct: cp_model_pb2.ConstraintProto
1205        # As with the IntVar::__init__ method, we hack the __init__ method to
1206        # support two use cases:
1207        #   case 1: called when creating a new interval variable.
1208        #      {start|size|end} are linear expressions, is_present_index is either
1209        #      None or the index of a Boolean literal. name is a string
1210        #   case 2: called when querying an existing interval variable.
1211        #      start_index is an int, all parameters after are None.
1212        if isinstance(start, int):
1213            if size is not None:
1214                raise ValueError("size should be None")
1215            if end is not None:
1216                raise ValueError("end should be None")
1217            if is_present_index is not None:
1218                raise ValueError("is_present_index should be None")
1219            self.__index = cast(int, start)
1220            self.__ct = model.constraints[self.__index]
1221        else:
1222            self.__index = len(model.constraints)
1223            self.__ct = self.__model.constraints.add()
1224            if start is None:
1225                raise TypeError("start is not defined")
1226            self.__ct.interval.start.CopyFrom(start)
1227            if size is None:
1228                raise TypeError("size is not defined")
1229            self.__ct.interval.size.CopyFrom(size)
1230            if end is None:
1231                raise TypeError("end is not defined")
1232            self.__ct.interval.end.CopyFrom(end)
1233            if is_present_index is not None:
1234                self.__ct.enforcement_literal.append(is_present_index)
1235            if name:
1236                self.__ct.name = name
1237
1238    @property
1239    def index(self) -> int:
1240        """Returns the index of the interval constraint in the model."""
1241        return self.__index
1242
1243    @property
1244    def proto(self) -> cp_model_pb2.IntervalConstraintProto:
1245        """Returns the interval protobuf."""
1246        return self.__ct.interval
1247
1248    def __str__(self):
1249        return self.__ct.name
1250
1251    def __repr__(self):
1252        interval = self.__ct.interval
1253        if self.__ct.enforcement_literal:
1254            return "%s(start = %s, size = %s, end = %s, is_present = %s)" % (
1255                self.__ct.name,
1256                short_expr_name(self.__model, interval.start),
1257                short_expr_name(self.__model, interval.size),
1258                short_expr_name(self.__model, interval.end),
1259                short_name(self.__model, self.__ct.enforcement_literal[0]),
1260            )
1261        else:
1262            return "%s(start = %s, size = %s, end = %s)" % (
1263                self.__ct.name,
1264                short_expr_name(self.__model, interval.start),
1265                short_expr_name(self.__model, interval.size),
1266                short_expr_name(self.__model, interval.end),
1267            )
1268
1269    @property
1270    def name(self) -> str:
1271        if not self.__ct or not self.__ct.name:
1272            return ""
1273        return self.__ct.name
1274
1275    def start_expr(self) -> LinearExprT:
1276        return LinearExpr.rebuild_from_linear_expression_proto(
1277            self.__model, self.__ct.interval.start
1278        )
1279
1280    def size_expr(self) -> LinearExprT:
1281        return LinearExpr.rebuild_from_linear_expression_proto(
1282            self.__model, self.__ct.interval.size
1283        )
1284
1285    def end_expr(self) -> LinearExprT:
1286        return LinearExpr.rebuild_from_linear_expression_proto(
1287            self.__model, self.__ct.interval.end
1288        )
1289
1290    # Pre PEP8 compatibility.
1291    # pylint: disable=invalid-name
1292    def Name(self) -> str:
1293        return self.name
1294
1295    def Index(self) -> int:
1296        return self.index
1297
1298    def Proto(self) -> cp_model_pb2.IntervalConstraintProto:
1299        return self.proto

1305    # pylint: enable=invalid-name

Represents an Interval variable.

An interval variable is both a constraint and a variable. It is defined by three integer variables: start, size, and end.

It is a constraint because, internally, it enforces that start + size == end.

It is also a variable as it can appear in specific scheduling constraints: NoOverlap, NoOverlap2D, Cumulative.

Optionally, an enforcement literal can be added to this constraint, in which case these scheduling constraints will ignore interval variables with enforcement literals assigned to false. Conversely, these constraints will also set these enforcement literals to false if they cannot fit these intervals into the schedule.

Raises:
  • ValueError: if start, size, end are not defined, or have the wrong type.
IntervalVar( model: ortools.sat.cp_model_pb2.CpModelProto, start: Union[ortools.sat.cp_model_pb2.LinearExpressionProto, int], size: Optional[ortools.sat.cp_model_pb2.LinearExpressionProto], end: Optional[ortools.sat.cp_model_pb2.LinearExpressionProto], is_present_index: Optional[int], name: Optional[str])

1206        # support two use cases:
1207        #   case 1: called when creating a new interval variable.
1208        #      {start|size|end} are linear expressions, is_present_index is either
1209        #      None or the index of a Boolean literal. name is a string
1210        #   case 2: called when querying an existing interval variable.
1211        #      start_index is an int, all parameters after are None.
1212        if isinstance(start, int):
1213            if size is not None:
1214                raise ValueError("size should be None")
1215            if end is not None:
1216                raise ValueError("end should be None")
1217            if is_present_index is not None:
1218                raise ValueError("is_present_index should be None")
1219            self.__index = cast(int, start)
1220            self.__ct = model.constraints[self.__index]
1221        else:
1222            self.__index = len(model.constraints)
1223            self.__ct = self.__model.constraints.add()
1224            if start is None:
1225                raise TypeError("start is not defined")
1226            self.__ct.interval.start.CopyFrom(start)
1227            if size is None:
1228                raise TypeError("size is not defined")
1229            self.__ct.interval.size.CopyFrom(size)
1230            if end is None:
1231                raise TypeError("end is not defined")
1232            self.__ct.interval.end.CopyFrom(end)
1233            if is_present_index is not None:
1234                self.__ct.enforcement_literal.append(is_present_index)
1235            if name:
1236                self.__ct.name = name

1241        return self.__index

def object_is_a_true_literal( literal: Union[IntVar, ortools.sat.python.cp_model._NotBooleanVariable, int, numpy.int8, numpy.uint8, numpy.int32, numpy.uint32, numpy.int64, numpy.uint64, bool]) -> bool: 
1308def object_is_a_true_literal(literal: LiteralT) -> bool:
1309    """Checks if literal is either True, or a Boolean literals fixed to True."""
1310    if isinstance(literal, IntVar):
1311        proto = literal.proto
1312        return len(proto.domain) == 2 and proto.domain[0] == 1 and proto.domain[1] == 1
1313    if isinstance(literal, _NotBooleanVariable):
1314        proto = literal.negated().proto
1315        return len(proto.domain) == 2 and proto.domain[0] == 0 and proto.domain[1] == 0
1316    if isinstance(literal, IntegralTypes):
1317        return int(literal) == 1
1318    return False

Checks if literal is either True, or a Boolean literals fixed to True.

def object_is_a_false_literal( literal: Union[IntVar, ortools.sat.python.cp_model._NotBooleanVariable, int, numpy.int8, numpy.uint8, numpy.int32, numpy.uint32, numpy.int64, numpy.uint64, bool]) -> bool: 
1321def object_is_a_false_literal(literal: LiteralT) -> bool:
1322    """Checks if literal is either False, or a Boolean literals fixed to False."""
1323    if isinstance(literal, IntVar):
1324        proto = literal.proto
1325        return len(proto.domain) == 2 and proto.domain[0] == 0 and proto.domain[1] == 0
1326    if isinstance(literal, _NotBooleanVariable):
1327        proto = literal.negated().proto
1328        return len(proto.domain) == 2 and proto.domain[0] == 1 and proto.domain[1] == 1
1329    if isinstance(literal, IntegralTypes):
1330        return int(literal) == 0
1331    return False

1362    def new_int_var(self, lb: IntegralT, ub: IntegralT, name: str) -> IntVar:
1363        """Create an integer variable with domain [lb, ub].
1364
1365        The CP-SAT solver is limited to integer variables. If you have fractional
1366        values, scale them up so that they become integers; if you have strings,
1367        encode them as integers.
1368
1369        Args:
1370          lb: Lower bound for the variable.
1371          ub: Upper bound for the variable.
1372          name: The name of the variable.
1373
1374        Returns:
1375          a variable whose domain is [lb, ub].
1376        """
1377
1378        return IntVar(self.__model, sorted_interval_list.Domain(lb, ub), name)
1379
1380    def new_int_var_from_domain(
1381        self, domain: sorted_interval_list.Domain, name: str
1382    ) -> IntVar:
1383        """Create an integer variable from a domain.
1384
1385        A domain is a set of integers specified by a collection of intervals.
1386        For example, `model.new_int_var_from_domain(cp_model.
1387             Domain.from_intervals([[1, 2], [4, 6]]), 'x')`
1388
1389        Args:
1390          domain: An instance of the Domain class.
1391          name: The name of the variable.
1392
1393        Returns:
1394            a variable whose domain is the given domain.
1395        """
1396        return IntVar(self.__model, domain, name)
1397
1398    def new_bool_var(self, name: str) -> IntVar:
1399        """Creates a 0-1 variable with the given name."""
1400        return IntVar(self.__model, sorted_interval_list.Domain(0, 1), name)

1403        """Declares a constant integer."""
1404        return IntVar(self.__model, self.get_or_make_index_from_constant(value), None)

1406    def new_int_var_series(
1407        self,
1408        name: str,
1409        index: pd.Index,
1410        lower_bounds: Union[IntegralT, pd.Series],
1411        upper_bounds: Union[IntegralT, pd.Series],
1412    ) -> pd.Series:
1413        """Creates a series of (scalar-valued) variables with the given name.
1414
1415        Args:
1416          name (str): Required. The name of the variable set.
1417          index (pd.Index): Required. The index to use for the variable set.
1418          lower_bounds (Union[int, pd.Series]): A lower bound for variables in the
1419            set. If a `pd.Series` is passed in, it will be based on the
1420            corresponding values of the pd.Series.
1421          upper_bounds (Union[int, pd.Series]): An upper bound for variables in the
1422            set. If a `pd.Series` is passed in, it will be based on the
1423            corresponding values of the pd.Series.
1424
1425        Returns:
1426          pd.Series: The variable set indexed by its corresponding dimensions.
1427
1428        Raises:
1429          TypeError: if the `index` is invalid (e.g. a `DataFrame`).
1430          ValueError: if the `name` is not a valid identifier or already exists.
1431          ValueError: if the `lowerbound` is greater than the `upperbound`.
1432          ValueError: if the index of `lower_bound`, or `upper_bound` does not match
1433          the input index.
1434        """
1435        if not isinstance(index, pd.Index):
1436            raise TypeError("Non-index object is used as index")
1437        if not name.isidentifier():
1438            raise ValueError("name={} is not a valid identifier".format(name))
1439        if (
1440            isinstance(lower_bounds, IntegralTypes)
1441            and isinstance(upper_bounds, IntegralTypes)
1442            and lower_bounds > upper_bounds
1443        ):
1444            raise ValueError(
1445                f"lower_bound={lower_bounds} is greater than"
1446                f" upper_bound={upper_bounds} for variable set={name}"
1447            )
1448
1449        lower_bounds = _convert_to_integral_series_and_validate_index(
1450            lower_bounds, index
1451        )
1452        upper_bounds = _convert_to_integral_series_and_validate_index(
1453            upper_bounds, index
1454        )
1455        return pd.Series(
1456            index=index,
1457            data=[
1458                # pylint: disable=g-complex-comprehension
1459                IntVar(
1460                    model=self.__model,
1461                    name=f"{name}[{i}]",
1462                    domain=sorted_interval_list.Domain(
1463                        lower_bounds[i], upper_bounds[i]
1464                    ),
1465                )
1466                for i in index
1467            ],
1468        )
1469
1470    def new_bool_var_series(
1471        self,
1472        name: str,
1473        index: pd.Index,
1474    ) -> pd.Series:
1475        """Creates a series of (scalar-valued) variables with the given name.
1476
1477        Args:
1478          name (str): Required. The name of the variable set.
1479          index (pd.Index): Required. The index to use for the variable set.
1480
1481        Returns:
1482          pd.Series: The variable set indexed by its corresponding dimensions.
1483
1484        Raises:
1485          TypeError: if the `index` is invalid (e.g. a `DataFrame`).
1486          ValueError: if the `name` is not a valid identifier or already exists.
1487        """
1488        return self.new_int_var_series(
1489            name=name, index=index, lower_bounds=0, upper_bounds=1
1490        )

1492    # Linear constraints.
1493
1494    def add_linear_constraint(
1495        self, linear_expr: LinearExprT, lb: IntegralT, ub: IntegralT
1496    ) -> Constraint:
1497        """Adds the constraint: `lb <= linear_expr <= ub`."""
1498        return self.add_linear_expression_in_domain(
1499            linear_expr, sorted_interval_list.Domain(lb, ub)
1500        )
1501
1502    def add_linear_expression_in_domain(
1503        self, linear_expr: LinearExprT, domain: sorted_interval_list.Domain
1504    ) -> Constraint:
1505        """Adds the constraint: `linear_expr` in `domain`."""
1506        if isinstance(linear_expr, LinearExpr):
1507            ct = Constraint(self)
1508            model_ct = self.__model.constraints[ct.index]
1509            coeffs_map, constant = linear_expr.get_integer_var_value_map()
1510            for t in coeffs_map.items():
1511                if not isinstance(t[0], IntVar):
1512                    raise TypeError("Wrong argument" + str(t))
1513                c = cmh.assert_is_int64(t[1])
1514                model_ct.linear.vars.append(t[0].index)
1515                model_ct.linear.coeffs.append(c)
1516            model_ct.linear.domain.extend(
1517                [
1518                    cmh.capped_subtraction(x, constant)
1519                    for x in domain.flattened_intervals()
1520                ]
1521            )
1522            return ct
1523        if isinstance(linear_expr, IntegralTypes):
1524            if not domain.contains(int(linear_expr)):
1525                return self.add_bool_or([])  # Evaluate to false.
1526            else:
1527                return self.add_bool_and([])  # Evaluate to true.
1528        raise TypeError(
1529            "not supported: CpModel.add_linear_expression_in_domain("
1530            + str(linear_expr)
1531            + " "
1532            + str(domain)
1533            + ")"
1534        )
1535
1536    @overload
1537    def add(self, ct: BoundedLinearExpression) -> Constraint: ...
1538
1539    @overload
1540    def add(self, ct: Union[bool, np.bool_]) -> Constraint: ...
1541
1542    def add(self, ct):
1543        """Adds a `BoundedLinearExpression` to the model.
1544
1545        Args:
1546          ct: A [`BoundedLinearExpression`](#boundedlinearexpression).
1547
1548        Returns:
1549          An instance of the `Constraint` class.
1550        """
1551        if isinstance(ct, BoundedLinearExpression):
1552            return self.add_linear_expression_in_domain(
1553                ct.expression(),
1554                sorted_interval_list.Domain.from_flat_intervals(ct.bounds()),
1555            )
1556        if ct and cmh.is_boolean(ct):
1557            return self.add_bool_or([True])
1558        if not ct and cmh.is_boolean(ct):
1559            return self.add_bool_or([])  # Evaluate to false.
1560        raise TypeError("not supported: CpModel.add(" + str(ct) + ")")
1561
1562    # General Integer Constraints.
1563
1564    @overload
1565    def add_all_different(self, expressions: Iterable[LinearExprT]) -> Constraint: ...
1566
1567    @overload
1568    def add_all_different(self, *expressions: LinearExprT) -> Constraint: ...
1569
1570    def add_all_different(self, *expressions):
1571        """Adds AllDifferent(expressions).
1572
1573        This constraint forces all expressions to have different values.
1574
1575        Args:
1576          *expressions: simple expressions of the form a * var + constant.
1577
1578        Returns:
1579          An instance of the `Constraint` class.
1580        """
1581        ct = Constraint(self)
1582        model_ct = self.__model.constraints[ct.index]
1583        expanded = expand_generator_or_tuple(expressions)
1584        model_ct.all_diff.exprs.extend(
1585            self.parse_linear_expression(x) for x in expanded
1586        )
1587        return ct
1588
1589    def add_element(
1590        self, index: VariableT, variables: Sequence[VariableT], target: VariableT
1591    ) -> Constraint:
1592        """Adds the element constraint: `variables[index] == target`.
1593
1594        Args:
1595          index: The index of the variable that's being constrained.
1596          variables: A list of variables.
1597          target: The value that the variable must be equal to.
1598
1599        Returns:
1600          An instance of the `Constraint` class.
1601        """
1602
1603        if not variables:
1604            raise ValueError("add_element expects a non-empty variables array")
1605
1606        if isinstance(index, IntegralTypes):
1607            variable: VariableT = list(variables)[int(index)]
1608            return self.add(variable == target)
1609
1610        ct = Constraint(self)
1611        model_ct = self.__model.constraints[ct.index]
1612        model_ct.element.index = self.get_or_make_index(index)
1613        model_ct.element.vars.extend([self.get_or_make_index(x) for x in variables])
1614        model_ct.element.target = self.get_or_make_index(target)
1615        return ct
1616
1617    def add_circuit(self, arcs: Sequence[ArcT]) -> Constraint:
1618        """Adds Circuit(arcs).
1619
1620        Adds a circuit constraint from a sparse list of arcs that encode the graph.
1621
1622        A circuit is a unique Hamiltonian path in a subgraph of the total
1623        graph. In case a node 'i' is not in the path, then there must be a
1624        loop arc 'i -> i' associated with a true literal. Otherwise
1625        this constraint will fail.
1626
1627        Args:
1628          arcs: a list of arcs. An arc is a tuple (source_node, destination_node,
1629            literal). The arc is selected in the circuit if the literal is true.
1630            Both source_node and destination_node must be integers between 0 and the
1631            number of nodes - 1.
1632
1633        Returns:
1634          An instance of the `Constraint` class.
1635
1636        Raises:
1637          ValueError: If the list of arcs is empty.
1638        """
1639        if not arcs:
1640            raise ValueError("add_circuit expects a non-empty array of arcs")
1641        ct = Constraint(self)
1642        model_ct = self.__model.constraints[ct.index]
1643        for arc in arcs:
1644            tail = cmh.assert_is_int32(arc[0])
1645            head = cmh.assert_is_int32(arc[1])
1646            lit = self.get_or_make_boolean_index(arc[2])
1647            model_ct.circuit.tails.append(tail)
1648            model_ct.circuit.heads.append(head)
1649            model_ct.circuit.literals.append(lit)
1650        return ct
1651
1652    def add_multiple_circuit(self, arcs: Sequence[ArcT]) -> Constraint:
1653        """Adds a multiple circuit constraint, aka the 'VRP' constraint.
1654
1655        The direct graph where arc #i (from tails[i] to head[i]) is present iff
1656        literals[i] is true must satisfy this set of properties:
1657        - #incoming arcs == 1 except for node 0.
1658        - #outgoing arcs == 1 except for node 0.
1659        - for node zero, #incoming arcs == #outgoing arcs.
1660        - There are no duplicate arcs.
1661        - Self-arcs are allowed except for node 0.
1662        - There is no cycle in this graph, except through node 0.
1663
1664        Args:
1665          arcs: a list of arcs. An arc is a tuple (source_node, destination_node,
1666            literal). The arc is selected in the circuit if the literal is true.
1667            Both source_node and destination_node must be integers between 0 and the
1668            number of nodes - 1.
1669
1670        Returns:
1671          An instance of the `Constraint` class.
1672
1673        Raises:
1674          ValueError: If the list of arcs is empty.
1675        """
1676        if not arcs:
1677            raise ValueError("add_multiple_circuit expects a non-empty array of arcs")
1678        ct = Constraint(self)
1679        model_ct = self.__model.constraints[ct.index]
1680        for arc in arcs:
1681            tail = cmh.assert_is_int32(arc[0])
1682            head = cmh.assert_is_int32(arc[1])
1683            lit = self.get_or_make_boolean_index(arc[2])
1684            model_ct.routes.tails.append(tail)
1685            model_ct.routes.heads.append(head)
1686            model_ct.routes.literals.append(lit)
1687        return ct
1688
1689    def add_allowed_assignments(
1690        self,
1691        variables: Sequence[VariableT],
1692        tuples_list: Iterable[Sequence[IntegralT]],
1693    ) -> Constraint:
1694        """Adds AllowedAssignments(variables, tuples_list).
1695
1696        An AllowedAssignments constraint is a constraint on an array of variables,
1697        which requires that when all variables are assigned values, the resulting
1698        array equals one of the  tuples in `tuple_list`.
1699
1700        Args:
1701          variables: A list of variables.
1702          tuples_list: A list of admissible tuples. Each tuple must have the same
1703            length as the variables, and the ith value of a tuple corresponds to the
1704            ith variable.
1705
1706        Returns:
1707          An instance of the `Constraint` class.
1708
1709        Raises:
1710          TypeError: If a tuple does not have the same size as the list of
1711              variables.
1712          ValueError: If the array of variables is empty.
1713        """
1714
1715        if not variables:
1716            raise ValueError(
1717                "add_allowed_assignments expects a non-empty variables array"
1718            )
1719
1720        ct = Constraint(self)
1721        model_ct = self.__model.constraints[ct.index]
1722        model_ct.table.vars.extend([self.get_or_make_index(x) for x in variables])
1723        arity = len(variables)
1724        for t in tuples_list:
1725            if len(t) != arity:
1726                raise TypeError("Tuple " + str(t) + " has the wrong arity")
1727            ar = []
1728            for v in t:
1729                ar.append(cmh.assert_is_int64(v))
1730            model_ct.table.values.extend(ar)
1731        return ct
1732
1733    def add_forbidden_assignments(
1734        self,
1735        variables: Sequence[VariableT],
1736        tuples_list: Iterable[Sequence[IntegralT]],
1737    ) -> Constraint:
1738        """Adds add_forbidden_assignments(variables, [tuples_list]).
1739
1740        A ForbiddenAssignments constraint is a constraint on an array of variables
1741        where the list of impossible combinations is provided in the tuples list.
1742
1743        Args:
1744          variables: A list of variables.
1745          tuples_list: A list of forbidden tuples. Each tuple must have the same
1746            length as the variables, and the *i*th value of a tuple corresponds to
1747            the *i*th variable.
1748
1749        Returns:
1750          An instance of the `Constraint` class.
1751
1752        Raises:
1753          TypeError: If a tuple does not have the same size as the list of
1754                     variables.
1755          ValueError: If the array of variables is empty.
1756        """
1757
1758        if not variables:
1759            raise ValueError(
1760                "add_forbidden_assignments expects a non-empty variables array"
1761            )
1762
1763        index = len(self.__model.constraints)
1764        ct = self.add_allowed_assignments(variables, tuples_list)
1765        self.__model.constraints[index].table.negated = True
1766        return ct
1767
1768    def add_automaton(
1769        self,
1770        transition_variables: Sequence[VariableT],
1771        starting_state: IntegralT,
1772        final_states: Sequence[IntegralT],
1773        transition_triples: Sequence[Tuple[IntegralT, IntegralT, IntegralT]],
1774    ) -> Constraint:
1775        """Adds an automaton constraint.
1776
1777        An automaton constraint takes a list of variables (of size *n*), an initial
1778        state, a set of final states, and a set of transitions. A transition is a
1779        triplet (*tail*, *transition*, *head*), where *tail* and *head* are states,
1780        and *transition* is the label of an arc from *head* to *tail*,
1781        corresponding to the value of one variable in the list of variables.
1782
1783        This automaton will be unrolled into a flow with *n* + 1 phases. Each phase
1784        contains the possible states of the automaton. The first state contains the
1785        initial state. The last phase contains the final states.
1786
1787        Between two consecutive phases *i* and *i* + 1, the automaton creates a set
1788        of arcs. For each transition (*tail*, *transition*, *head*), it will add
1789        an arc from the state *tail* of phase *i* and the state *head* of phase
1790        *i* + 1. This arc is labeled by the value *transition* of the variables
1791        `variables[i]`. That is, this arc can only be selected if `variables[i]`
1792        is assigned the value *transition*.
1793
1794        A feasible solution of this constraint is an assignment of variables such
1795        that, starting from the initial state in phase 0, there is a path labeled by
1796        the values of the variables that ends in one of the final states in the
1797        final phase.
1798
1799        Args:
1800          transition_variables: A non-empty list of variables whose values
1801            correspond to the labels of the arcs traversed by the automaton.
1802          starting_state: The initial state of the automaton.
1803          final_states: A non-empty list of admissible final states.
1804          transition_triples: A list of transitions for the automaton, in the
1805            following format (current_state, variable_value, next_state).
1806
1807        Returns:
1808          An instance of the `Constraint` class.
1809
1810        Raises:
1811          ValueError: if `transition_variables`, `final_states`, or
1812            `transition_triples` are empty.
1813        """
1814
1815        if not transition_variables:
1816            raise ValueError(
1817                "add_automaton expects a non-empty transition_variables array"
1818            )
1819        if not final_states:
1820            raise ValueError("add_automaton expects some final states")
1821
1822        if not transition_triples:
1823            raise ValueError("add_automaton expects some transition triples")
1824
1825        ct = Constraint(self)
1826        model_ct = self.__model.constraints[ct.index]
1827        model_ct.automaton.vars.extend(
1828            [self.get_or_make_index(x) for x in transition_variables]
1829        )
1830        starting_state = cmh.assert_is_int64(starting_state)
1831        model_ct.automaton.starting_state = starting_state
1832        for v in final_states:
1833            v = cmh.assert_is_int64(v)
1834            model_ct.automaton.final_states.append(v)
1835        for t in transition_triples:
1836            if len(t) != 3:
1837                raise TypeError("Tuple " + str(t) + " has the wrong arity (!= 3)")
1838            tail = cmh.assert_is_int64(t[0])
1839            label = cmh.assert_is_int64(t[1])
1840            head = cmh.assert_is_int64(t[2])
1841            model_ct.automaton.transition_tail.append(tail)
1842            model_ct.automaton.transition_label.append(label)
1843            model_ct.automaton.transition_head.append(head)
1844        return ct
1845
1846    def add_inverse(
1847        self,
1848        variables: Sequence[VariableT],
1849        inverse_variables: Sequence[VariableT],
1850    ) -> Constraint:
1851        """Adds Inverse(variables, inverse_variables).
1852
1853        An inverse constraint enforces that if `variables[i]` is assigned a value
1854        `j`, then `inverse_variables[j]` is assigned a value `i`. And vice versa.
1855
1856        Args:
1857          variables: An array of integer variables.
1858          inverse_variables: An array of integer variables.
1859
1860        Returns:
1861          An instance of the `Constraint` class.
1862
1863        Raises:
1864          TypeError: if variables and inverse_variables have different lengths, or
1865              if they are empty.
1866        """
1867
1868        if not variables or not inverse_variables:
1869            raise TypeError("The Inverse constraint does not accept empty arrays")
1870        if len(variables) != len(inverse_variables):
1871            raise TypeError(
1872                "In the inverse constraint, the two array variables and"
1873                " inverse_variables must have the same length."
1874            )
1875        ct = Constraint(self)
1876        model_ct = self.__model.constraints[ct.index]
1877        model_ct.inverse.f_direct.extend([self.get_or_make_index(x) for x in variables])
1878        model_ct.inverse.f_inverse.extend(
1879            [self.get_or_make_index(x) for x in inverse_variables]
1880        )
1881        return ct
1882
1883    def add_reservoir_constraint(
1884        self,
1885        times: Iterable[LinearExprT],
1886        level_changes: Iterable[LinearExprT],
1887        min_level: int,
1888        max_level: int,
1889    ) -> Constraint:
1890        """Adds Reservoir(times, level_changes, min_level, max_level).
1891
1892        Maintains a reservoir level within bounds. The water level starts at 0, and
1893        at any time, it must be between min_level and max_level.
1894
1895        If the affine expression `times[i]` is assigned a value t, then the current
1896        level changes by `level_changes[i]`, which is constant, at time t.
1897
1898         Note that min level must be <= 0, and the max level must be >= 0. Please
1899         use fixed level_changes to simulate initial state.
1900
1901         Therefore, at any time:
1902             sum(level_changes[i] if times[i] <= t) in [min_level, max_level]
1903
1904        Args:
1905          times: A list of 1-var affine expressions (a * x + b) which specify the
1906            time of the filling or emptying the reservoir.
1907          level_changes: A list of integer values that specifies the amount of the
1908            emptying or filling. Currently, variable demands are not supported.
1909          min_level: At any time, the level of the reservoir must be greater or
1910            equal than the min level.
1911          max_level: At any time, the level of the reservoir must be less or equal
1912            than the max level.
1913
1914        Returns:
1915          An instance of the `Constraint` class.
1916
1917        Raises:
1918          ValueError: if max_level < min_level.
1919
1920          ValueError: if max_level < 0.
1921
1922          ValueError: if min_level > 0
1923        """
1924
1925        if max_level < min_level:
1926            raise ValueError("Reservoir constraint must have a max_level >= min_level")
1927
1928        if max_level < 0:
1929            raise ValueError("Reservoir constraint must have a max_level >= 0")
1930
1931        if min_level > 0:
1932            raise ValueError("Reservoir constraint must have a min_level <= 0")
1933
1934        ct = Constraint(self)
1935        model_ct = self.__model.constraints[ct.index]
1936        model_ct.reservoir.time_exprs.extend(
1937            [self.parse_linear_expression(x) for x in times]
1938        )
1939        model_ct.reservoir.level_changes.extend(
1940            [self.parse_linear_expression(x) for x in level_changes]
1941        )
1942        model_ct.reservoir.min_level = min_level
1943        model_ct.reservoir.max_level = max_level
1944        return ct
1945
1946    def add_reservoir_constraint_with_active(
1947        self,
1948        times: Iterable[LinearExprT],
1949        level_changes: Iterable[LinearExprT],
1950        actives: Iterable[LiteralT],
1951        min_level: int,
1952        max_level: int,
1953    ) -> Constraint:
1954        """Adds Reservoir(times, level_changes, actives, min_level, max_level).
1955
1956        Maintains a reservoir level within bounds. The water level starts at 0, and
1957        at any time, it must be between min_level and max_level.
1958
1959        If the variable `times[i]` is assigned a value t, and `actives[i]` is
1960        `True`, then the current level changes by `level_changes[i]`, which is
1961        constant,
1962        at time t.
1963
1964         Note that min level must be <= 0, and the max level must be >= 0. Please
1965         use fixed level_changes to simulate initial state.
1966
1967         Therefore, at any time:
1968             sum(level_changes[i] * actives[i] if times[i] <= t) in [min_level,
1969             max_level]
1970
1971
1972        The array of boolean variables 'actives', if defined, indicates which
1973        actions are actually performed.
1974
1975        Args:
1976          times: A list of 1-var affine expressions (a * x + b) which specify the
1977            time of the filling or emptying the reservoir.
1978          level_changes: A list of integer values that specifies the amount of the
1979            emptying or filling. Currently, variable demands are not supported.
1980          actives: a list of boolean variables. They indicates if the
1981            emptying/refilling events actually take place.
1982          min_level: At any time, the level of the reservoir must be greater or
1983            equal than the min level.
1984          max_level: At any time, the level of the reservoir must be less or equal
1985            than the max level.
1986
1987        Returns:
1988          An instance of the `Constraint` class.
1989
1990        Raises:
1991          ValueError: if max_level < min_level.
1992
1993          ValueError: if max_level < 0.
1994
1995          ValueError: if min_level > 0
1996        """
1997
1998        if max_level < min_level:
1999            raise ValueError("Reservoir constraint must have a max_level >= min_level")
2000
2001        if max_level < 0:
2002            raise ValueError("Reservoir constraint must have a max_level >= 0")
2003
2004        if min_level > 0:
2005            raise ValueError("Reservoir constraint must have a min_level <= 0")
2006
2007        ct = Constraint(self)
2008        model_ct = self.__model.constraints[ct.index]
2009        model_ct.reservoir.time_exprs.extend(
2010            [self.parse_linear_expression(x) for x in times]
2011        )
2012        model_ct.reservoir.level_changes.extend(
2013            [self.parse_linear_expression(x) for x in level_changes]
2014        )
2015        model_ct.reservoir.active_literals.extend(
2016            [self.get_or_make_boolean_index(x) for x in actives]
2017        )
2018        model_ct.reservoir.min_level = min_level
2019        model_ct.reservoir.max_level = max_level
2020        return ct
2021
2022    def add_map_domain(
2023        self, var: IntVar, bool_var_array: Iterable[IntVar], offset: IntegralT = 0
2024    ):
2025        """Adds `var == i + offset <=> bool_var_array[i] == true for all i`."""
2026
2027        for i, bool_var in enumerate(bool_var_array):
2028            b_index = bool_var.index
2029            var_index = var.index
2030            model_ct = self.__model.constraints.add()
2031            model_ct.linear.vars.append(var_index)
2032            model_ct.linear.coeffs.append(1)
2033            offset_as_int = int(offset)
2034            model_ct.linear.domain.extend([offset_as_int + i, offset_as_int + i])
2035            model_ct.enforcement_literal.append(b_index)
2036
2037            model_ct = self.__model.constraints.add()
2038            model_ct.linear.vars.append(var_index)
2039            model_ct.linear.coeffs.append(1)
2040            model_ct.enforcement_literal.append(-b_index - 1)
2041            if offset + i - 1 >= INT_MIN:
2042                model_ct.linear.domain.extend([INT_MIN, offset_as_int + i - 1])
2043            if offset + i + 1 <= INT_MAX:
2044                model_ct.linear.domain.extend([offset_as_int + i + 1, INT_MAX])
2045
2046    def add_implication(self, a: LiteralT, b: LiteralT) -> Constraint:
2047        """Adds `a => b` (`a` implies `b`)."""
2048        ct = Constraint(self)
2049        model_ct = self.__model.constraints[ct.index]
2050        model_ct.bool_or.literals.append(self.get_or_make_boolean_index(b))
2051        model_ct.enforcement_literal.append(self.get_or_make_boolean_index(a))
2052        return ct

2234    # Scheduling support
2235
2236    def new_interval_var(
2237        self, start: LinearExprT, size: LinearExprT, end: LinearExprT, name: str
2238    ) -> IntervalVar:
2239        """Creates an interval variable from start, size, and end.
2240
2241        An interval variable is a constraint, that is itself used in other
2242        constraints like NoOverlap.
2243
2244        Internally, it ensures that `start + size == end`.
2245
2246        Args:
2247          start: The start of the interval. It must be of the form a * var + b.
2248          size: The size of the interval. It must be of the form a * var + b.
2249          end: The end of the interval. It must be of the form a * var + b.
2250          name: The name of the interval variable.
2251
2252        Returns:
2253          An `IntervalVar` object.
2254        """
2255
2256        start_expr = self.parse_linear_expression(start)
2257        size_expr = self.parse_linear_expression(size)
2258        end_expr = self.parse_linear_expression(end)
2259        if len(start_expr.vars) > 1:
2260            raise TypeError(
2261                "cp_model.new_interval_var: start must be 1-var affine or constant."
2262            )
2263        if len(size_expr.vars) > 1:
2264            raise TypeError(
2265                "cp_model.new_interval_var: size must be 1-var affine or constant."
2266            )
2267        if len(end_expr.vars) > 1:
2268            raise TypeError(
2269                "cp_model.new_interval_var: end must be 1-var affine or constant."
2270            )
2271        return IntervalVar(self.__model, start_expr, size_expr, end_expr, None, name)
2272
2273    def new_interval_var_series(
2274        self,
2275        name: str,
2276        index: pd.Index,
2277        starts: Union[LinearExprT, pd.Series],
2278        sizes: Union[LinearExprT, pd.Series],
2279        ends: Union[LinearExprT, pd.Series],
2280    ) -> pd.Series:
2281        """Creates a series of interval variables with the given name.
2282
2283        Args:
2284          name (str): Required. The name of the variable set.
2285          index (pd.Index): Required. The index to use for the variable set.
2286          starts (Union[LinearExprT, pd.Series]): The start of each interval in the
2287            set. If a `pd.Series` is passed in, it will be based on the
2288            corresponding values of the pd.Series.
2289          sizes (Union[LinearExprT, pd.Series]): The size of each interval in the
2290            set. If a `pd.Series` is passed in, it will be based on the
2291            corresponding values of the pd.Series.
2292          ends (Union[LinearExprT, pd.Series]): The ends of each interval in the
2293            set. If a `pd.Series` is passed in, it will be based on the
2294            corresponding values of the pd.Series.
2295
2296        Returns:
2297          pd.Series: The interval variable set indexed by its corresponding
2298          dimensions.
2299
2300        Raises:
2301          TypeError: if the `index` is invalid (e.g. a `DataFrame`).
2302          ValueError: if the `name` is not a valid identifier or already exists.
2303          ValueError: if the all the indexes do not match.
2304        """
2305        if not isinstance(index, pd.Index):
2306            raise TypeError("Non-index object is used as index")
2307        if not name.isidentifier():
2308            raise ValueError("name={} is not a valid identifier".format(name))
2309
2310        starts = _convert_to_linear_expr_series_and_validate_index(starts, index)
2311        sizes = _convert_to_linear_expr_series_and_validate_index(sizes, index)
2312        ends = _convert_to_linear_expr_series_and_validate_index(ends, index)
2313        interval_array = []
2314        for i in index:
2315            interval_array.append(
2316                self.new_interval_var(
2317                    start=starts[i],
2318                    size=sizes[i],
2319                    end=ends[i],
2320                    name=f"{name}[{i}]",
2321                )
2322            )
2323        return pd.Series(index=index, data=interval_array)
2324
2325    def new_fixed_size_interval_var(
2326        self, start: LinearExprT, size: IntegralT, name: str
2327    ) -> IntervalVar:
2328        """Creates an interval variable from start, and a fixed size.
2329
2330        An interval variable is a constraint, that is itself used in other
2331        constraints like NoOverlap.
2332
2333        Args:
2334          start: The start of the interval. It must be of the form a * var + b.
2335          size: The size of the interval. It must be an integer value.
2336          name: The name of the interval variable.
2337
2338        Returns:
2339          An `IntervalVar` object.
2340        """
2341        size = cmh.assert_is_int64(size)
2342        start_expr = self.parse_linear_expression(start)
2343        size_expr = self.parse_linear_expression(size)
2344        end_expr = self.parse_linear_expression(start + size)
2345        if len(start_expr.vars) > 1:
2346            raise TypeError(
2347                "cp_model.new_interval_var: start must be affine or constant."
2348            )
2349        return IntervalVar(self.__model, start_expr, size_expr, end_expr, None, name)
2350
2351    def new_fixed_size_interval_var_series(
2352        self,
2353        name: str,
2354        index: pd.Index,
2355        starts: Union[LinearExprT, pd.Series],
2356        sizes: Union[IntegralT, pd.Series],
2357    ) -> pd.Series:
2358        """Creates a series of interval variables with the given name.
2359
2360        Args:
2361          name (str): Required. The name of the variable set.
2362          index (pd.Index): Required. The index to use for the variable set.
2363          starts (Union[LinearExprT, pd.Series]): The start of each interval in the
2364            set. If a `pd.Series` is passed in, it will be based on the
2365            corresponding values of the pd.Series.
2366          sizes (Union[IntegralT, pd.Series]): The fixed size of each interval in
2367            the set. If a `pd.Series` is passed in, it will be based on the
2368            corresponding values of the pd.Series.
2369
2370        Returns:
2371          pd.Series: The interval variable set indexed by its corresponding
2372          dimensions.
2373
2374        Raises:
2375          TypeError: if the `index` is invalid (e.g. a `DataFrame`).
2376          ValueError: if the `name` is not a valid identifier or already exists.
2377          ValueError: if the all the indexes do not match.
2378        """
2379        if not isinstance(index, pd.Index):
2380            raise TypeError("Non-index object is used as index")
2381        if not name.isidentifier():
2382            raise ValueError("name={} is not a valid identifier".format(name))
2383
2384        starts = _convert_to_linear_expr_series_and_validate_index(starts, index)
2385        sizes = _convert_to_integral_series_and_validate_index(sizes, index)
2386        interval_array = []
2387        for i in index:
2388            interval_array.append(
2389                self.new_fixed_size_interval_var(
2390                    start=starts[i],
2391                    size=sizes[i],
2392                    name=f"{name}[{i}]",
2393                )
2394            )
2395        return pd.Series(index=index, data=interval_array)

2397    def new_optional_interval_var(
2398        self,
2399        start: LinearExprT,
2400        size: LinearExprT,
2401        end: LinearExprT,
2402        is_present: LiteralT,
2403        name: str,
2404    ) -> IntervalVar:
2405        """Creates an optional interval var from start, size, end, and is_present.
2406
2407        An optional interval variable is a constraint, that is itself used in other
2408        constraints like NoOverlap. This constraint is protected by a presence
2409        literal that indicates if it is active or not.
2410
2411        Internally, it ensures that `is_present` implies `start + size ==
2412        end`.
2413
2414        Args:
2415          start: The start of the interval. It must be of the form a * var + b.
2416          size: The size of the interval. It must be of the form a * var + b.
2417          end: The end of the interval. It must be of the form a * var + b.
2418          is_present: A literal that indicates if the interval is active or not. A
2419            inactive interval is simply ignored by all constraints.
2420          name: The name of the interval variable.
2421
2422        Returns:
2423          An `IntervalVar` object.
2424        """
2425
2426        # Creates the IntervalConstraintProto object.
2427        is_present_index = self.get_or_make_boolean_index(is_present)
2428        start_expr = self.parse_linear_expression(start)
2429        size_expr = self.parse_linear_expression(size)
2430        end_expr = self.parse_linear_expression(end)
2431        if len(start_expr.vars) > 1:
2432            raise TypeError(
2433                "cp_model.new_interval_var: start must be affine or constant."
2434            )
2435        if len(size_expr.vars) > 1:
2436            raise TypeError(
2437                "cp_model.new_interval_var: size must be affine or constant."
2438            )
2439        if len(end_expr.vars) > 1:
2440            raise TypeError(
2441                "cp_model.new_interval_var: end must be affine or constant."
2442            )
2443        return IntervalVar(
2444            self.__model, start_expr, size_expr, end_expr, is_present_index, name
2445        )
2446
2447    def new_optional_interval_var_series(
2448        self,
2449        name: str,
2450        index: pd.Index,
2451        starts: Union[LinearExprT, pd.Series],
2452        sizes: Union[LinearExprT, pd.Series],
2453        ends: Union[LinearExprT, pd.Series],
2454        are_present: Union[LiteralT, pd.Series],
2455    ) -> pd.Series:
2456        """Creates a series of interval variables with the given name.
2457
2458        Args:
2459          name (str): Required. The name of the variable set.
2460          index (pd.Index): Required. The index to use for the variable set.
2461          starts (Union[LinearExprT, pd.Series]): The start of each interval in the
2462            set. If a `pd.Series` is passed in, it will be based on the
2463            corresponding values of the pd.Series.
2464          sizes (Union[LinearExprT, pd.Series]): The size of each interval in the
2465            set. If a `pd.Series` is passed in, it will be based on the
2466            corresponding values of the pd.Series.
2467          ends (Union[LinearExprT, pd.Series]): The ends of each interval in the
2468            set. If a `pd.Series` is passed in, it will be based on the
2469            corresponding values of the pd.Series.
2470          are_present (Union[LiteralT, pd.Series]): The performed literal of each
2471            interval in the set. If a `pd.Series` is passed in, it will be based on
2472            the corresponding values of the pd.Series.
2473
2474        Returns:
2475          pd.Series: The interval variable set indexed by its corresponding
2476          dimensions.
2477
2478        Raises:
2479          TypeError: if the `index` is invalid (e.g. a `DataFrame`).
2480          ValueError: if the `name` is not a valid identifier or already exists.
2481          ValueError: if the all the indexes do not match.
2482        """
2483        if not isinstance(index, pd.Index):
2484            raise TypeError("Non-index object is used as index")
2485        if not name.isidentifier():
2486            raise ValueError("name={} is not a valid identifier".format(name))
2487
2488        starts = _convert_to_linear_expr_series_and_validate_index(starts, index)
2489        sizes = _convert_to_linear_expr_series_and_validate_index(sizes, index)
2490        ends = _convert_to_linear_expr_series_and_validate_index(ends, index)
2491        are_present = _convert_to_literal_series_and_validate_index(are_present, index)
2492
2493        interval_array = []
2494        for i in index:
2495            interval_array.append(
2496                self.new_optional_interval_var(
2497                    start=starts[i],
2498                    size=sizes[i],
2499                    end=ends[i],
2500                    is_present=are_present[i],
2501                    name=f"{name}[{i}]",
2502                )
2503            )
2504        return pd.Series(index=index, data=interval_array)
2505
2506    def new_optional_fixed_size_interval_var(
2507        self,
2508        start: LinearExprT,
2509        size: IntegralT,
2510        is_present: LiteralT,
2511        name: str,
2512    ) -> IntervalVar:
2513        """Creates an interval variable from start, and a fixed size.
2514
2515        An interval variable is a constraint, that is itself used in other
2516        constraints like NoOverlap.
2517
2518        Args:
2519          start: The start of the interval. It must be of the form a * var + b.
2520          size: The size of the interval. It must be an integer value.
2521          is_present: A literal that indicates if the interval is active or not. A
2522            inactive interval is simply ignored by all constraints.
2523          name: The name of the interval variable.
2524
2525        Returns:
2526          An `IntervalVar` object.
2527        """
2528        size = cmh.assert_is_int64(size)
2529        start_expr = self.parse_linear_expression(start)
2530        size_expr = self.parse_linear_expression(size)
2531        end_expr = self.parse_linear_expression(start + size)
2532        if len(start_expr.vars) > 1:
2533            raise TypeError(
2534                "cp_model.new_interval_var: start must be affine or constant."
2535            )
2536        is_present_index = self.get_or_make_boolean_index(is_present)
2537        return IntervalVar(
2538            self.__model,
2539            start_expr,
2540            size_expr,
2541            end_expr,
2542            is_present_index,
2543            name,
2544        )
2545
2546    def new_optional_fixed_size_interval_var_series(
2547        self,
2548        name: str,
2549        index: pd.Index,
2550        starts: Union[LinearExprT, pd.Series],
2551        sizes: Union[IntegralT, pd.Series],
2552        are_present: Union[LiteralT, pd.Series],
2553    ) -> pd.Series:
2554        """Creates a series of interval variables with the given name.
2555
2556        Args:
2557          name (str): Required. The name of the variable set.
2558          index (pd.Index): Required. The index to use for the variable set.
2559          starts (Union[LinearExprT, pd.Series]): The start of each interval in the
2560            set. If a `pd.Series` is passed in, it will be based on the
2561            corresponding values of the pd.Series.
2562          sizes (Union[IntegralT, pd.Series]): The fixed size of each interval in
2563            the set. If a `pd.Series` is passed in, it will be based on the
2564            corresponding values of the pd.Series.
2565          are_present (Union[LiteralT, pd.Series]): The performed literal of each
2566            interval in the set. If a `pd.Series` is passed in, it will be based on
2567            the corresponding values of the pd.Series.
2568
2569        Returns:
2570          pd.Series: The interval variable set indexed by its corresponding
2571          dimensions.
2572
2573        Raises:
2574          TypeError: if the `index` is invalid (e.g. a `DataFrame`).
2575          ValueError: if the `name` is not a valid identifier or already exists.
2576          ValueError: if the all the indexes do not match.
2577        """
2578        if not isinstance(index, pd.Index):
2579            raise TypeError("Non-index object is used as index")
2580        if not name.isidentifier():
2581            raise ValueError("name={} is not a valid identifier".format(name))
2582
2583        starts = _convert_to_linear_expr_series_and_validate_index(starts, index)
2584        sizes = _convert_to_integral_series_and_validate_index(sizes, index)
2585        are_present = _convert_to_literal_series_and_validate_index(are_present, index)
2586        interval_array = []
2587        for i in index:
2588            interval_array.append(
2589                self.new_optional_fixed_size_interval_var(
2590                    start=starts[i],
2591                    size=sizes[i],
2592                    is_present=are_present[i],
2593                    name=f"{name}[{i}]",
2594                )
2595            )
2596        return pd.Series(index=index, data=interval_array)
2597
2598    def add_no_overlap(self, interval_vars: Iterable[IntervalVar]) -> Constraint:
2599        """Adds NoOverlap(interval_vars).
2600
2601        A NoOverlap constraint ensures that all present intervals do not overlap
2602        in time.
2603
2604        Args:
2605          interval_vars: The list of interval variables to constrain.
2606
2607        Returns:
2608          An instance of the `Constraint` class.
2609        """
2610        ct = Constraint(self)
2611        model_ct = self.__model.constraints[ct.index]
2612        model_ct.no_overlap.intervals.extend(
2613            [self.get_interval_index(x) for x in interval_vars]
2614        )
2615        return ct
2616
2617    def add_no_overlap_2d(
2618        self,
2619        x_intervals: Iterable[IntervalVar],
2620        y_intervals: Iterable[IntervalVar],
2621    ) -> Constraint:
2622        """Adds NoOverlap2D(x_intervals, y_intervals).
2623
2624        A NoOverlap2D constraint ensures that all present rectangles do not overlap
2625        on a plane. Each rectangle is aligned with the X and Y axis, and is defined
2626        by two intervals which represent its projection onto the X and Y axis.
2627
2628        Furthermore, one box is optional if at least one of the x or y interval is
2629        optional.
2630
2631        Args:
2632          x_intervals: The X coordinates of the rectangles.
2633          y_intervals: The Y coordinates of the rectangles.
2634
2635        Returns:
2636          An instance of the `Constraint` class.
2637        """
2638        ct = Constraint(self)
2639        model_ct = self.__model.constraints[ct.index]
2640        model_ct.no_overlap_2d.x_intervals.extend(
2641            [self.get_interval_index(x) for x in x_intervals]
2642        )
2643        model_ct.no_overlap_2d.y_intervals.extend(
2644            [self.get_interval_index(x) for x in y_intervals]
2645        )
2646        return ct
2647
2648    def add_cumulative(
2649        self,
2650        intervals: Iterable[IntervalVar],
2651        demands: Iterable[LinearExprT],
2652        capacity: LinearExprT,
2653    ) -> Constraint:
2654        """Adds Cumulative(intervals, demands, capacity).
2655
2656        This constraint enforces that:
2657
2658            for all t:
2659              sum(demands[i]
2660                if (start(intervals[i]) <= t < end(intervals[i])) and
2661                (intervals[i] is present)) <= capacity
2662
2663        Args:
2664          intervals: The list of intervals.
2665          demands: The list of demands for each interval. Each demand must be >= 0.
2666            Each demand can be a 1-var affine expression (a * x + b).
2667          capacity: The maximum capacity of the cumulative constraint. It can be a
2668            1-var affine expression (a * x + b).
2669
2670        Returns:
2671          An instance of the `Constraint` class.
2672        """
2673        cumulative = Constraint(self)
2674        model_ct = self.__model.constraints[cumulative.index]
2675        model_ct.cumulative.intervals.extend(
2676            [self.get_interval_index(x) for x in intervals]
2677        )
2678        for d in demands:
2679            model_ct.cumulative.demands.append(self.parse_linear_expression(d))
2680        model_ct.cumulative.capacity.CopyFrom(self.parse_linear_expression(capacity))
2681        return cumulative
2682
2683    # Support for model cloning.
2684    def clone(self) -> "CpModel":
2685        """Reset the model, and creates a new one from a CpModelProto instance."""
2686        clone = CpModel()
2687        clone.proto.CopyFrom(self.proto)
2688        clone.rebuild_constant_map()
2689        return clone
2690
2691    def rebuild_constant_map(self):
2692        """Internal method used during model cloning."""
2693        for i, var in enumerate(self.__model.variables):
2694            if len(var.domain) == 2 and var.domain[0] == var.domain[1]:
2695                self.__constant_map[var.domain[0]] = i
2696
2697    def get_bool_var_from_proto_index(self, index: int) -> IntVar:
2698        """Returns an already created Boolean variable from its index."""
2699        if index < 0 or index >= len(self.__model.variables):
2700            raise ValueError(
2701                f"get_bool_var_from_proto_index: out of bound index {index}"
2702            )
2703        var = self.__model.variables[index]
2704        if len(var.domain) != 2 or var.domain[0] < 0 or var.domain[1] > 1:
2705            raise ValueError(
2706                f"get_bool_var_from_proto_index: index {index} does not reference"
2707                + " a Boolean variable"
2708            )
2709
2710        return IntVar(self.__model, index, None)
2711
2712    def get_int_var_from_proto_index(self, index: int) -> IntVar:
2713        """Returns an already created integer variable from its index."""
2714        if index < 0 or index >= len(self.__model.variables):
2715            raise ValueError(
2716                f"get_int_var_from_proto_index: out of bound index {index}"
2717            )
2718        return IntVar(self.__model, index, None)
2719
2720    def get_interval_var_from_proto_index(self, index: int) -> IntervalVar:
2721        """Returns an already created interval variable from its index."""
2722        if index < 0 or index >= len(self.__model.constraints):
2723            raise ValueError(
2724                f"get_interval_var_from_proto_index: out of bound index {index}"
2725            )
2726        ct = self.__model.constraints[index]
2727        if not ct.HasField("interval"):
2728            raise ValueError(
2729                f"get_interval_var_from_proto_index: index {index} does not"
2730                " reference an" + " interval variable"
2731            )
2732
2733        return IntervalVar(self.__model, index, None, None, None, None)
2734
2735    # Helpers.
2736
2737    def __str__(self):
2738        return str(self.__model)
2739
2740    @property
2741    def proto(self) -> cp_model_pb2.CpModelProto:
2742        """Returns the underlying CpModelProto."""
2743        return self.__model
2744
2745    def negated(self, index: int) -> int:
2746        return -index - 1
2747
2748    def get_or_make_index(self, arg: VariableT) -> int:
2749        """Returns the index of a variable, its negation, or a number."""
2750        if isinstance(arg, IntVar):
2751            return arg.index
2752        if (
2753            isinstance(arg, _ProductCst)
2754            and isinstance(arg.expression(), IntVar)
2755            and arg.coefficient() == -1
2756        ):
2757            return -arg.expression().index - 1
2758        if isinstance(arg, IntegralTypes):
2759            arg = cmh.assert_is_int64(arg)
2760            return self.get_or_make_index_from_constant(arg)
2761        raise TypeError("NotSupported: model.get_or_make_index(" + str(arg) + ")")
2762
2763    def get_or_make_boolean_index(self, arg: LiteralT) -> int:
2764        """Returns an index from a boolean expression."""
2765        if isinstance(arg, IntVar):
2766            self.assert_is_boolean_variable(arg)
2767            return arg.index
2768        if isinstance(arg, _NotBooleanVariable):
2769            self.assert_is_boolean_variable(arg.negated())
2770            return arg.index
2771        if isinstance(arg, IntegralTypes):
2772            arg = cmh.assert_is_zero_or_one(arg)
2773            return self.get_or_make_index_from_constant(arg)
2774        if cmh.is_boolean(arg):
2775            return self.get_or_make_index_from_constant(int(arg))
2776        raise TypeError(f"not supported: model.get_or_make_boolean_index({arg})")
2777
2778    def get_interval_index(self, arg: IntervalVar) -> int:
2779        if not isinstance(arg, IntervalVar):
2780            raise TypeError("NotSupported: model.get_interval_index(%s)" % arg)
2781        return arg.index
2782
2783    def get_or_make_index_from_constant(self, value: IntegralT) -> int:
2784        if value in self.__constant_map:
2785            return self.__constant_map[value]
2786        index = len(self.__model.variables)
2787        self.__model.variables.add(domain=[value, value])
2788        self.__constant_map[value] = index
2789        return index
2790
2791    def var_index_to_var_proto(
2792        self, var_index: int
2793    ) -> cp_model_pb2.IntegerVariableProto:
2794        if var_index >= 0:
2795            return self.__model.variables[var_index]
2796        else:
2797            return self.__model.variables[-var_index - 1]
2798
2799    def parse_linear_expression(
2800        self, linear_expr: LinearExprT, negate: bool = False
2801    ) -> cp_model_pb2.LinearExpressionProto:
2802        """Returns a LinearExpressionProto built from a LinearExpr instance."""
2803        result: cp_model_pb2.LinearExpressionProto = (
2804            cp_model_pb2.LinearExpressionProto()
2805        )
2806        mult = -1 if negate else 1
2807        if isinstance(linear_expr, IntegralTypes):
2808            result.offset = int(linear_expr) * mult
2809            return result
2810
2811        if isinstance(linear_expr, IntVar):
2812            result.vars.append(self.get_or_make_index(linear_expr))
2813            result.coeffs.append(mult)
2814            return result
2815
2816        coeffs_map, constant = cast(LinearExpr, linear_expr).get_integer_var_value_map()
2817        result.offset = constant * mult
2818        for t in coeffs_map.items():
2819            if not isinstance(t[0], IntVar):
2820                raise TypeError("Wrong argument" + str(t))
2821            c = cmh.assert_is_int64(t[1])
2822            result.vars.append(t[0].index)
2823            result.coeffs.append(c * mult)
2824        return result
2825
2826    def _set_objective(self, obj: ObjLinearExprT, minimize: bool):
2827        """Sets the objective of the model."""
2828        self.clear_objective()
2829        if isinstance(obj, IntVar):
2830            self.__model.objective.vars.append(obj.index)
2831            self.__model.objective.offset = 0
2832            if minimize:
2833                self.__model.objective.coeffs.append(1)
2834                self.__model.objective.scaling_factor = 1
2835            else:
2836                self.__model.objective.coeffs.append(-1)
2837                self.__model.objective.scaling_factor = -1
2838        elif isinstance(obj, LinearExpr):
2839            coeffs_map, constant, is_integer = obj.get_float_var_value_map()
2840            if is_integer:
2841                if minimize:
2842                    self.__model.objective.scaling_factor = 1
2843                    self.__model.objective.offset = constant
2844                else:
2845                    self.__model.objective.scaling_factor = -1
2846                    self.__model.objective.offset = -constant
2847                for v, c in coeffs_map.items():
2848                    c_as_int = int(c)
2849                    self.__model.objective.vars.append(v.index)
2850                    if minimize:
2851                        self.__model.objective.coeffs.append(c_as_int)
2852                    else:
2853                        self.__model.objective.coeffs.append(-c_as_int)
2854            else:
2855                self.__model.floating_point_objective.maximize = not minimize
2856                self.__model.floating_point_objective.offset = constant
2857                for v, c in coeffs_map.items():
2858                    self.__model.floating_point_objective.coeffs.append(c)
2859                    self.__model.floating_point_objective.vars.append(v.index)
2860        elif isinstance(obj, IntegralTypes):
2861            self.__model.objective.offset = int(obj)
2862            self.__model.objective.scaling_factor = 1
2863        else:
2864            raise TypeError("TypeError: " + str(obj) + " is not a valid objective")
2865
2866    def minimize(self, obj: ObjLinearExprT):
2867        """Sets the objective of the model to minimize(obj)."""
2868        self._set_objective(obj, minimize=True)
2869
2870    def maximize(self, obj: ObjLinearExprT):
2871        """Sets the objective of the model to maximize(obj)."""
2872        self._set_objective(obj, minimize=False)
2873
2874    def has_objective(self) -> bool:
2875        return self.__model.HasField("objective") or self.__model.HasField(
2876            "floating_point_objective"
2877        )
2878
2879    def clear_objective(self):
2880        self.__model.ClearField("objective")
2881        self.__model.ClearField("floating_point_objective")
2882
2883    def add_decision_strategy(
2884        self,
2885        variables: Sequence[IntVar],
2886        var_strategy: cp_model_pb2.DecisionStrategyProto.VariableSelectionStrategy,
2887        domain_strategy: cp_model_pb2.DecisionStrategyProto.DomainReductionStrategy,
2888    ) -> None:
2889        """Adds a search strategy to the model.
2890
2891        Args:
2892          variables: a list of variables this strategy will assign.
2893          var_strategy: heuristic to choose the next variable to assign.
2894          domain_strategy: heuristic to reduce the domain of the selected variable.
2895            Currently, this is advanced code: the union of all strategies added to
2896            the model must be complete, i.e. instantiates all variables. Otherwise,
2897            solve() will fail.
2898        """
2899
2900        strategy: cp_model_pb2.DecisionStrategyProto = (
2901            self.__model.search_strategy.add()
2902        )
2903        for v in variables:
2904            expr = strategy.exprs.add()
2905            if v.index >= 0:
2906                expr.vars.append(v.index)
2907                expr.coeffs.append(1)
2908            else:
2909                expr.vars.append(self.negated(v.index))
2910                expr.coeffs.append(-1)
2911                expr.offset = 1
2912
2913        strategy.variable_selection_strategy = var_strategy
2914        strategy.domain_reduction_strategy = domain_strategy
2915
2916    def model_stats(self) -> str:
2917        """Returns a string containing some model statistics."""
2918        return swig_helper.CpSatHelper.model_stats(self.__model)
2919
2920    def validate(self) -> str:
2921        """Returns a string indicating that the model is invalid."""
2922        return swig_helper.CpSatHelper.validate_model(self.__model)
2923
2924    def export_to_file(self, file: str) -> bool:
2925        """Write the model as a protocol buffer to 'file'.
2926
2927        Args:
2928          file: file to write the model to. If the filename ends with 'txt', the
2929            model will be written as a text file, otherwise, the binary format will
2930            be used.
2931
2932        Returns:
2933          True if the model was correctly written.
2934        """
2935        return swig_helper.CpSatHelper.write_model_to_file(self.__model, file)
2936
2937    def add_hint(self, var: IntVar, value: int) -> None:
2938        """Adds 'var == value' as a hint to the solver."""
2939        self.__model.solution_hint.vars.append(self.get_or_make_index(var))
2940        self.__model.solution_hint.values.append(value)
2941
2942    def clear_hints(self):
2943        """Removes any solution hint from the model."""
2944        self.__model.ClearField("solution_hint")
2945
2946    def add_assumption(self, lit: LiteralT) -> None:
2947        """Adds the literal to the model as assumptions."""
2948        self.__model.assumptions.append(self.get_or_make_boolean_index(lit))
2949
2950    def add_assumptions(self, literals: Iterable[LiteralT]) -> None:
2951        """Adds the literals to the model as assumptions."""
2952        for lit in literals:
2953            self.add_assumption(lit)
2954
2955    def clear_assumptions(self) -> None:
2956        """Removes all assumptions from the model."""
2957        self.__model.ClearField("assumptions")
2958
2959    # Helpers.
2960    def assert_is_boolean_variable(self, x: LiteralT) -> None:
2961        if isinstance(x, IntVar):
2962            var = self.__model.variables[x.index]
2963            if len(var.domain) != 2 or var.domain[0] < 0 or var.domain[1] > 1:
2964                raise TypeError("TypeError: " + str(x) + " is not a boolean variable")
2965        elif not isinstance(x, _NotBooleanVariable):
2966            raise TypeError("TypeError: " + str(x) + " is not a boolean variable")
2967
2968    # Compatibility with pre PEP8
2969    # pylint: disable=invalid-name
2970
2971    def Name(self) -> str:

def new_int_var_series( self, name: str, index: pandas.core.indexes.base.Index, lower_bounds: Union[int, numpy.int8, numpy.uint8, numpy.int32, numpy.uint32, numpy.int64, numpy.uint64, pandas.core.series.Series], upper_bounds: Union[int, numpy.int8, numpy.uint8, numpy.int32, numpy.uint32, numpy.int64, numpy.uint64, pandas.core.series.Series]) -> pandas.core.series.Series: 
1406    def new_int_var_series(
1407        self,
1408        name: str,
1409        index: pd.Index,
1410        lower_bounds: Union[IntegralT, pd.Series],
1411        upper_bounds: Union[IntegralT, pd.Series],
1412    ) -> pd.Series:
1413        """Creates a series of (scalar-valued) variables with the given name.
1414
1415        Args:
1416          name (str): Required. The name of the variable set.
1417          index (pd.Index): Required. The index to use for the variable set.
1418          lower_bounds (Union[int, pd.Series]): A lower bound for variables in the
1419            set. If a `pd.Series` is passed in, it will be based on the
1420            corresponding values of the pd.Series.
1421          upper_bounds (Union[int, pd.Series]): An upper bound for variables in the
1422            set. If a `pd.Series` is passed in, it will be based on the
1423            corresponding values of the pd.Series.
1424
1425        Returns:
1426          pd.Series: The variable set indexed by its corresponding dimensions.
1427
1428        Raises:
1429          TypeError: if the `index` is invalid (e.g. a `DataFrame`).
1430          ValueError: if the `name` is not a valid identifier or already exists.
1431          ValueError: if the `lowerbound` is greater than the `upperbound`.
1432          ValueError: if the index of `lower_bound`, or `upper_bound` does not match
1433          the input index.
1434        """
1435        if not isinstance(index, pd.Index):
1436            raise TypeError("Non-index object is used as index")
1437        if not name.isidentifier():
1438            raise ValueError("name={} is not a valid identifier".format(name))
1439        if (
1440            isinstance(lower_bounds, IntegralTypes)
1441            and isinstance(upper_bounds, IntegralTypes)
1442            and lower_bounds > upper_bounds
1443        ):
1444            raise ValueError(
1445                f"lower_bound={lower_bounds} is greater than"
1446                f" upper_bound={upper_bounds} for variable set={name}"
1447            )
1448
1449        lower_bounds = _convert_to_integral_series_and_validate_index(
1450            lower_bounds, index
1451        )
1452        upper_bounds = _convert_to_integral_series_and_validate_index(
1453            upper_bounds, index
1454        )
1455        return pd.Series(
1456            index=index,
1457            data=[
1458                # pylint: disable=g-complex-comprehension
1459                IntVar(
1460                    model=self.__model,
1461                    name=f"{name}[{i}]",
1462                    domain=sorted_interval_list.Domain(
1463                        lower_bounds[i], upper_bounds[i]
1464                    ),
1465                )
1466                for i in index
1467            ],
1468        )

Creates a series of (scalar-valued) variables with the given name.

Arguments:
  • name (str): Required. The name of the variable set.
  • index (pd.Index): Required. The index to use for the variable set.
  • lower_bounds (Union[int, pd.Series]): A lower bound for variables in the set. If a pd.Series is passed in, it will be based on the corresponding values of the pd.Series.
  • upper_bounds (Union[int, pd.Series]): An upper bound for variables in the set. If a pd.Series is passed in, it will be based on the corresponding values of the pd.Series.

pd.Series: The variable set indexed by its corresponding dimensions.

def add_linear_expression_in_domain( self, linear_expr: Union[LinearExpr, IntVar, int, numpy.int8, numpy.uint8, numpy.int32, numpy.uint32, numpy.int64, numpy.uint64], domain: Domain) -> Constraint: 
1502    def add_linear_expression_in_domain(
1503        self, linear_expr: LinearExprT, domain: sorted_interval_list.Domain
1504    ) -> Constraint:
1505        """Adds the constraint: `linear_expr` in `domain`."""
1506        if isinstance(linear_expr, LinearExpr):
1507            ct = Constraint(self)
1508            model_ct = self.__model.constraints[ct.index]
1509            coeffs_map, constant = linear_expr.get_integer_var_value_map()
1510            for t in coeffs_map.items():
1511                if not isinstance(t[0], IntVar):
1512                    raise TypeError("Wrong argument" + str(t))
1513                c = cmh.assert_is_int64(t[1])
1514                model_ct.linear.vars.append(t[0].index)
1515                model_ct.linear.coeffs.append(c)
1516            model_ct.linear.domain.extend(
1517                [
1518                    cmh.capped_subtraction(x, constant)
1519                    for x in domain.flattened_intervals()
1520                ]
1521            )
1522            return ct
1523        if isinstance(linear_expr, IntegralTypes):
1524            if not domain.contains(int(linear_expr)):
1525                return self.add_bool_or([])  # Evaluate to false.
1526            else:
1527                return self.add_bool_and([])  # Evaluate to true.
1528        raise TypeError(
1529            "not supported: CpModel.add_linear_expression_in_domain("
1530            + str(linear_expr)
1531            + " "
1532            + str(domain)
1533            + ")"
1534        )

Adds the constraint: linear_expr in domain.

def add(self, ct): 
1542    def add(self, ct):
1543        """Adds a `BoundedLinearExpression` to the model.
1544
1545        Args:
1546          ct: A [`BoundedLinearExpression`](#boundedlinearexpression).
1547
1548        Returns:
1549          An instance of the `Constraint` class.
1550        """
1551        if isinstance(ct, BoundedLinearExpression):
1552            return self.add_linear_expression_in_domain(
1553                ct.expression(),
1554                sorted_interval_list.Domain.from_flat_intervals(ct.bounds()),
1555            )
1556        if ct and cmh.is_boolean(ct):
1557            return self.add_bool_or([True])
1558        if not ct and cmh.is_boolean(ct):
1559            return self.add_bool_or([])  # Evaluate to false.
1560        raise TypeError("not supported: CpModel.add(" + str(ct) + ")")
